2
00:01:35,595 --> 00:01:40,191
J. L... Yes, J. L... Yes, J.L.

3
00:01:44,204 --> 00:01:46,798
- I've been waiting a half-hour!
- Not now, Mel. I'm busy.

4
00:01:47,006 --> 00:01:48,803
Got to get all his sons-in-law
on the phone.

5
00:01:49,008 --> 00:01:50,635
Main, 674.

6
00:01:50,844 --> 00:01:54,041
Board of directors' meeting tonight.
This is the 1 st, you know.

7
00:01:54,247 --> 00:01:55,680
They all know it's the 1 st.

8
00:01:55,882 --> 00:01:58,783
They know there's a meeting tonight.
The whole town knows it.

9
00:01:58,985 --> 00:02:00,247
Higgins Iron Works?

10
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:03,889
Higgins, Higgins, Higgins.

11
00:02:06,159 --> 00:02:07,683
That's not a family,

12
00:02:07,894 --> 00:02:09,623
it's a disease!

13
00:02:13,333 --> 00:02:15,392
Arthur Winslow talking.

14
00:02:15,702 --> 00:02:18,500
Oh, yes, Mrs. Peterson. Yes.

15
00:02:18,705 --> 00:02:21,037
I just want to remind you there's
a board of directors' meeting

16
00:02:21,241 --> 00:02:23,072
at J.L.'s house tonight
at 7 sharp.

17
00:02:26,179 --> 00:02:28,579
Oh, yes, Mrs. Peterson.

18
00:02:29,315 --> 00:02:31,408
Oh, you know me,
"Never Late" Early.

19
00:02:34,554 --> 00:02:37,990
No, Mrs. Peterson, Mr. Brooks
hasn't been in all day.

20
00:02:38,658 --> 00:02:39,989
I don't know.

21
00:02:40,193 --> 00:02:42,559
It's got to be cut lower.
I've told you 100 times, lower!

22
00:02:42,762 --> 00:02:44,855
Madame, I told you 200 times,
there's a limitation.

23
00:02:45,064 --> 00:02:46,497
There will be at least
1,000 people...

24
00:02:46,699 --> 00:02:48,291
All right. So what?
It's my wedding, not my funeral!

25
00:02:48,501 --> 00:02:50,059
- Who is it?
- Your father's secretary.

26
00:02:50,270 --> 00:02:52,431
What does that old bag want? Hello?

27
00:02:52,639 --> 00:02:54,231
Well, how do I know where
Dan Brooks is?

28
00:02:54,440 --> 00:02:55,668
Please help me locate him!

29
00:02:55,875 --> 00:02:58,639
You know how strict your father is
about the meetings.

30
00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:00,244
Well, he's not under my bed.

31
00:03:00,446 --> 00:03:03,074
All right, I'll get him to the meeting
as I got him to all the others.

32
00:03:03,283 --> 00:03:04,511
He's probably out
with that stupid horse.

33
00:03:05,051 --> 00:03:08,111
Come on, Whitey! You're heading
into the stretch. Let him roll!

34
00:03:08,321 --> 00:03:10,289
Come on! Let him roll!
Let's see if we got a horse.

35
00:03:10,490 --> 00:03:12,048
Kick it out of low, princess.
Come on.

36
00:03:12,258 --> 00:03:14,818
Oh, Bill. Oh, Bill. Come on, boy.

37
00:03:22,468 --> 00:03:23,696
- What'd he make it in?
- Huh?

38
00:03:23,903 --> 00:03:25,530
- What'd he make it in?
- 1:42.

39
00:03:25,738 --> 00:03:27,137
- Is that good?
- Good?

40
00:03:27,340 --> 00:03:30,036
Honey, on a cowpath like this,
for a 3-year-old, that's flying.

41
00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:31,972
Here, Bill. Come on, boy.

42
00:03:35,448 --> 00:03:37,746
Mr. Brooks, this animal
just ain't human.

43
00:03:37,951 --> 00:03:39,179
He's a flier, isn't he?

44
00:03:39,385 --> 00:03:40,750
- What'd he do it in?
- 1:42.

45
00:03:40,954 --> 00:03:42,182
Great day in a morning!

46
00:03:42,388 --> 00:03:44,913
With me on him?
He's diseased with speed.

47
00:03:45,124 --> 00:03:47,422
It's a nice way to be sick.
Isn't he a beauty, princess?

48
00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:50,721
Oh, you said it.
Oh, we're proud of you, Broadway Bill.

49
00:03:51,397 --> 00:03:52,694
Steady, Bill.

50
00:03:53,566 --> 00:03:55,966
- How's that ankle?
- Feels cool.

51
00:03:58,871 --> 00:04:00,930
- He made it.
- Well, what's this?

52
00:04:01,140 --> 00:04:03,608
- <i>Pathé</i> news comes to Higginsville?
- No, that's Skeeter.

53
00:04:03,810 --> 00:04:05,675
- Skeeter?
- Miss Alice taught him to do that.

54
00:04:05,878 --> 00:04:07,345
- I have many talents.
- Well!

55
00:04:07,547 --> 00:04:10,812
Broadway Bill, you got a mascot
like a stakes winner. Big stuff, huh?

56
00:04:11,017 --> 00:04:14,043
Is it true horses get so attached to
mascots they won't run without them?

57
00:04:14,254 --> 00:04:16,381
Yeah, that's true,
but I think a jockey's useful too.

58
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:19,057
Hey, Whitey, get those bandages off
and go to walking him, huh?

59
00:04:19,259 --> 00:04:22,490
Dan? When you put racing shoes
on him, can I help you?

60
00:04:22,695 --> 00:04:23,923
Huh?

61
00:04:24,130 --> 00:04:26,121
Say, you know more about
this horse than I do.

62
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:28,061
You been hanging around
the stable quite a bit, huh?

63
00:04:28,268 --> 00:04:29,496
Want to make something of it?

64
00:04:29,702 --> 00:04:31,135
No, but don't you let
Emperor Higgins catch you.

65
00:04:31,337 --> 00:04:32,804
He'll ship you off to the salt mines.

66
00:04:33,006 --> 00:04:35,065
Emperor Higgins
doesn't even know I'm alive.

67
00:04:35,275 --> 00:04:36,742
I'm just the young brat in the family.

68
00:04:36,943 --> 00:04:38,376
Well, you will stay single.

69
00:04:38,578 --> 00:04:40,273
Why don't you get married
and give him another son-in-law.

70
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:42,971
Yes, I know. Someone to take care
of another Higgins enterprise.

71
00:04:43,182 --> 00:04:44,410
Not little Alice.

72
00:04:44,617 --> 00:04:46,778
OK, but marriage is getting
popular, you know.

73
00:04:46,986 --> 00:04:49,477
I'm going to post soon.
Don't get shut out.

74
00:04:50,890 --> 00:04:53,051
Been a long time since I've seen
a horse work that good.

75
00:04:53,259 --> 00:04:54,590
Dan, why don't you?

76
00:04:54,794 --> 00:04:57,786
Yeah, I should. Why don't I what?

77
00:04:57,997 --> 00:04:59,760
Imperial Race Track
opened last week.

78
00:04:59,966 --> 00:05:02,366
Oh, no. No more of that hobo stuff
for Dan Brooks.

79
00:05:02,568 --> 00:05:04,593
He's getting married.
Gonna be a solid citizen.

80
00:05:04,804 --> 00:05:07,534
Don't do it, Dan. Don't marry a Higgins.
Don't marry any Higgins.

81
00:05:07,740 --> 00:05:09,867
You'll just rot here,
like the rest of us.

82
00:05:10,076 --> 00:05:11,941
Princess, you've got
a very attractive little nose,

83
00:05:12,145 --> 00:05:14,306
but keep it out of my business
or I'll twist it off for you.

84
00:05:14,514 --> 00:05:15,811
- You're a fool!
- Well, I'm a happy one.

85
00:05:16,015 --> 00:05:17,915
I was just a race track mug
till I met your sister.

86
00:05:18,117 --> 00:05:20,347
Now I'm general manager of
the Higgins Paper Box Company.

87
00:05:20,553 --> 00:05:22,418
Prune juice! You've been dying
to get out of Higginsville

88
00:05:22,622 --> 00:05:24,146
- ever since you came here.
- Oh, get her!

89
00:05:24,357 --> 00:05:26,882
Your heart and soul are in horses,
and you're making paper boxes.

90
00:05:27,093 --> 00:05:29,357
Four hundred thousand last month.
Or was it last year?

91
00:05:29,562 --> 00:05:31,621
- You're scared, that's what you are.
- Who's scared?

92
00:05:31,831 --> 00:05:33,389
Dan Brooks, horseman.

93
00:05:33,599 --> 00:05:35,829
Dan Brooks,
just another Higgins slave.

94
00:05:36,035 --> 00:05:39,732
Yeah? Well, at my salary,
slavery can come back.

95
00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:43,509
- Mr. Brooks, it ain't fair. It ain't honest.
- What ain't honest?

96
00:05:43,710 --> 00:05:45,735
- What do you mean?
- We been together for a long time,

97
00:05:45,945 --> 00:05:47,845
and this is the mostest horse
we ever did have!

98
00:05:48,047 --> 00:05:49,412
He's ready, Mr. Brooks.

99
00:05:49,615 --> 00:05:52,175
Just picked up that truck
with my last 25 bucks.

100
00:05:52,385 --> 00:05:55,377
He's ready. You know it better than
I do. We owe it to him. He's ready!

101
00:05:55,588 --> 00:05:58,079
Yes, he's ready and you're ready,
but I'm not. Do you hear?

102
00:05:58,291 --> 00:05:59,553
I got smart. I quit racing.

103
00:05:59,759 --> 00:06:01,556
I'm gonna stay smart.

104
00:06:03,096 --> 00:06:05,690
Hey, Bill, go on.

105
00:06:05,898 --> 00:06:08,662
Go on, chase him, chase him.
Chase him!

106
00:06:11,904 --> 00:06:14,065
Go on. That's it. Push him.

107
00:06:15,641 --> 00:06:19,042
No. Now, I'm through. No! Now, leave
me alone. I'm through with racing.

108
00:06:19,245 --> 00:06:22,078
Don't mess with me.
I'm a big paper-box man.

109
00:06:22,281 --> 00:06:24,112
Yeah, attaboy.

110
00:06:25,885 --> 00:06:27,648
Never mind, now. Break it up.

111
00:06:27,854 --> 00:06:29,446
Never mind.

112
00:06:32,492 --> 00:06:36,019
No, I don't want to play. No, I'm a big
business man. Gotta go to a meeting.

113
00:06:36,229 --> 00:06:38,390
You can stop that dancing too.

114
00:06:38,598 --> 00:06:41,431
I told you, I'm through with horses.
Go on! Go back to Whitey.

115
00:06:41,634 --> 00:06:43,693
Go with Whitey. I don't want anything
to do with you. Go on!

116
00:06:43,903 --> 00:06:45,871
Now go back. Give him some more.

117
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:47,630
Yeah, that's it.

118
00:06:48,207 --> 00:06:50,869
You back again?
What do you want with me?

119
00:06:51,077 --> 00:06:53,409
What do you want with me?
I'm through! I'm through with horses.

120
00:06:53,613 --> 00:06:56,309
Gonna make the paper boxes.
Yeah! Yeah!

121
00:06:59,218 --> 00:07:00,617
Now go give him some more.

122
00:07:00,820 --> 00:07:02,947
Why, I'll kick you in your big...

123
00:07:26,145 --> 00:07:28,545
- Good evening, Miss Margaret.
- Good evening. What is your name?

124
00:07:28,748 --> 00:07:30,045
- Huh?
- Is Mr. Brooks ready yet?

125
00:07:30,249 --> 00:07:33,685
Not quite.
The name is Clarence White.

126
00:07:43,429 --> 00:07:46,865
<i>Wort say that rivers flow</i>

127
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:50,795
<i>Or day turns to night</i>

128
00:07:51,437 --> 00:07:53,234
<i>But, darling</i>

129
00:07:53,439 --> 00:07:57,535
<i>I'd say we've got a sure thing</i>

130
00:07:57,743 --> 00:07:59,608
<i>All right</i>

131
00:08:00,780 --> 00:08:03,476
<i>Wort say it's winter</i>

132
00:08:03,683 --> 00:08:08,552
<i>When snow falls from above</i>

133
00:08:09,355 --> 00:08:11,516
<i>But, darling</i>

134
00:08:11,724 --> 00:08:15,558
<i>It's a sure thing we're</i>

135
00:08:16,195 --> 00:08:19,392
<i>In love</i>

136
00:08:19,699 --> 00:08:20,927
- Maggie!
- Darling!

137
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:22,862
Come here.

138
00:08:27,940 --> 00:08:30,238
We'll never get to the meeting this way.
Come on, slowpoke.

139
00:08:30,443 --> 00:08:33,241
Wait a minute.
Not so fast, me proud beauty.

140
00:08:33,446 --> 00:08:36,711
What's your hurry?
What's the rush?

141
00:08:37,583 --> 00:08:40,177
Anybody ever tell you you're
the most beautiful girl in the world?

142
00:08:40,386 --> 00:08:41,614
Just the world?

143
00:08:41,821 --> 00:08:46,019
I'll include all the available planets,
the stratosphere, the outer space,

144
00:08:46,225 --> 00:08:48,887
New York, New Haven and Hartford,
leaving on track five.

145
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:50,960
- That's better.
- Here.

146
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:52,425
- Come on.
- What's the hurry?

147
00:08:52,632 --> 00:08:53,929
Come on, darling.

148
00:08:54,133 --> 00:08:56,693
I may not be the most beautiful,
but I'm the happiest girl in the world.

149
00:08:56,903 --> 00:08:59,235
The invitations were mailed today,
and you should see my dress.

150
00:08:59,438 --> 00:09:01,668
- A stunner?
- Only three weeks more, darling.

151
00:09:01,874 --> 00:09:04,399
The wedding will be the biggest thing
since Texas joined the Union.

152
00:09:04,610 --> 00:09:06,703
- That was a big day.
- Good heavens!

153
00:09:06,913 --> 00:09:08,608
- Even your dinner jacket smells horsy!
- What?

154
00:09:08,814 --> 00:09:10,714
What do you use,
Equine No. 5?

155
00:09:10,917 --> 00:09:12,544
You know he worked
a mile in 1:42 today?

156
00:09:12,752 --> 00:09:13,980
- Who?
- Broadway Bill!

157
00:09:14,186 --> 00:09:16,416
And with Whitey on him too.
Just sitting there, looking and cooking.

158
00:09:16,622 --> 00:09:17,953
Why don't you come out
the next time he works.

159
00:09:18,157 --> 00:09:19,385
I'll bet if you knew him,
you'd love him.

160
00:09:19,592 --> 00:09:21,787
Oh, I like horses, all right.
Especially when they're racing.

161
00:09:21,994 --> 00:09:23,621
- Didrt I meet you at the track?
- That's what you did.

162
00:09:23,829 --> 00:09:26,229
Remember, when I leaned over
and asked you if you had a winner?

163
00:09:26,432 --> 00:09:29,595
Oh, and I had a winner too. You.

164
00:09:29,802 --> 00:09:31,429
- Ready?
- Sure, I'm ready. Flashy.

165
00:09:31,637 --> 00:09:33,468
What kind of socks
are you wearing this time?

166
00:09:35,608 --> 00:09:36,836
What difference does it make?

167
00:09:37,043 --> 00:09:39,011
Dan, you've got to change them.
Quickly, where are the black ones?

168
00:09:39,211 --> 00:09:40,940
They'll be under the table
all night anyhow.

169
00:09:41,147 --> 00:09:42,944
If you got to know
Broadway Bill personally,

170
00:09:43,149 --> 00:09:46,312
I'll bet you'd be crazy about him.
Did I ever tell you about his mother?

171
00:09:46,519 --> 00:09:47,884
- She was blind, you know?
- Blind?

172
00:09:48,087 --> 00:09:50,749
Yeah, stone-blind.
Beautifully bred mare, though.

173
00:09:50,957 --> 00:09:52,185
Put those on, and hurry.

174
00:09:52,391 --> 00:09:54,825
She had quite a problem
when the little colt arrived.

175
00:09:55,027 --> 00:09:57,154
Naturally, she wanted to be near him,
but she couldn't,

176
00:09:57,363 --> 00:09:59,558
because she couldn't find him.
It was pitiful to watch her.

177
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:03,360
She'd start in a little circle, and
the circle would get larger and larger.

178
00:10:03,569 --> 00:10:05,161
She'd cover every foot of that field,

179
00:10:05,371 --> 00:10:07,839
but that little rascal, he'd just stay
a step ahead of her all the time.

180
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:09,667
She couldn't reach him, and at night,

181
00:10:09,875 --> 00:10:11,866
boy, at night,
what a ruckus she'd raise!

182
00:10:12,078 --> 00:10:15,172
I'd have to get up, find Broadway Bill,
take him in to her. But I licked it.

183
00:10:15,381 --> 00:10:19,215
You know what I did? I got a bell.
An ordinary dinner bell.

184
00:10:19,418 --> 00:10:21,409
I tied it around his neck.
Solved her problem.

185
00:10:21,621 --> 00:10:23,816
- She'd hear the bell, find the colt.
- Clever.

186
00:10:24,023 --> 00:10:25,251
Put the other one on.

187
00:10:25,458 --> 00:10:27,119
After a while,
an amazing thing happened.

188
00:10:27,326 --> 00:10:29,624
You won't believe this,
but this is absolutely true.

189
00:10:29,829 --> 00:10:33,230
That little colt, he realized that
something was wrong with his mother.

190
00:10:33,432 --> 00:10:35,024
And he wouldn't leave her side.

191
00:10:35,234 --> 00:10:38,203
Gee, I can remember we used to turn
the colts and the mares out.

192
00:10:38,404 --> 00:10:40,429
They'd head lickety-split
for the field, just kicking,

193
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:44,337
playing, buckjumping,
but not Broadway Bill. No, sir.

194
00:10:44,543 --> 00:10:47,774
He'd stay with her, and he'd lead
her every step of the way, over rocks,

195
00:10:47,980 --> 00:10:51,040
around the ditches and the ruts
until he got her safely into the pasture.

196
00:10:51,250 --> 00:10:53,741
You'd just have to love a little egg
like that, wouldn't you?

197
00:10:53,953 --> 00:10:55,318
- I don't blame you.
- That's him.

198
00:10:55,521 --> 00:10:57,614
Out in the barn,
that's Broadway Bill!

199
00:10:58,157 --> 00:11:00,955
Well, then a lot of bad breaks
came along.

200
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:04,095
Couldrt win a race, horses got sick,
lost a few of them,

201
00:11:04,296 --> 00:11:06,093
and up to my ears in debts.

202
00:11:06,298 --> 00:11:08,823
Then you came along,
asked me if I had a winner.

203
00:11:10,036 --> 00:11:13,233
So in three days, I sold the whole kit
and caboodle of them, you remember?

204
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:15,930
Paid off my debts and proposed to you
every hour on the hour.

205
00:11:16,142 --> 00:11:19,600
Promised to quit racing
and followed you here to Higginsville,

206
00:11:19,812 --> 00:11:21,473
but I couldn't come without
Broadway Bill.

207
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:23,478
I figured maybe after
our kids grew up,

208
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:25,981
he'd make a nice little horse
for them to hack around on.

209
00:11:26,185 --> 00:11:28,710
Whitey... Couldrt leave old Whitey,

210
00:11:28,921 --> 00:11:31,754
not after all we'd been through
together, working and starving.

211
00:11:31,957 --> 00:11:34,084
So Broadway Bill's a 3-year-old now,
and he's a runner!

212
00:11:34,293 --> 00:11:37,091
- Maybe a great runner, Maggie.
- Oh, it's a wonderful story, darling.

213
00:11:37,296 --> 00:11:38,991
But, as you say,
you're through with racing.

214
00:11:39,198 --> 00:11:40,893
And if you think that old mare's
got a problem,

215
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:43,466
I've gotta get you to that meeting
on time or be disowned. Come on!

216
00:11:43,669 --> 00:11:45,500
Maggie, wait, wait.
Let's duck the meeting tonight.

217
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:46,933
- Duck the meeting?
- Yeah. Let's you and I

218
00:11:47,139 --> 00:11:49,039
go somewhere and just sit
under the moon together and talk.

219
00:11:49,241 --> 00:11:50,469
I want to talk about a few things.

220
00:11:50,676 --> 00:11:52,871
Father would throw a royal fit.
You know we've got to go.

221
00:11:53,079 --> 00:11:55,570
Why? What difference does it make?
He does all the talking anyhow.

222
00:11:55,781 --> 00:11:57,339
We just sit there
with our heads on hinges.

223
00:11:57,550 --> 00:12:00,747
"Yes, J.L. Of course, J.L.
Oh, you're so right, J.L."

224
00:12:00,953 --> 00:12:03,217
I'd like to go to one of those meetings
with a stiff neck sometime.

225
00:12:03,422 --> 00:12:05,617
- Throw the whole thing out of tempo.
- Oh, Dan, stop.

226
00:12:05,825 --> 00:12:08,953
Father has great plans for you.
That's why the others are all so jealous.

227
00:12:09,161 --> 00:12:11,959
Yeah, "the others". Look, let's go over
and stand in front of the house

228
00:12:12,164 --> 00:12:13,563
and throw rocks at the meeting.
What do you say?

229
00:12:13,766 --> 00:12:16,234
- Dan, it's almost 7.
- Well, do you want to throw rocks?

230
00:12:16,435 --> 00:12:18,130
No. And neither would you
if you had any sense.

231
00:12:18,337 --> 00:12:20,737
Remember, you'll be calling those
meetings someday. Now, come on!

232
00:12:20,940 --> 00:12:23,170
We can't afford to be late again.
You know Father. Come on!

233
00:12:23,375 --> 00:12:24,603
"Yes, J.L. Yes, J.L."

234
00:12:27,246 --> 00:12:29,009
- Good evening, Mrs. Early.
- Good evening, Johnson.

235
00:12:29,215 --> 00:12:30,978
- Good evening, Johnson.
- Mr. Early.

236
00:12:31,417 --> 00:12:33,977
- J.L.'s in the study.
- Thank you, Johnson.

237
00:12:34,186 --> 00:12:37,781
Well, right on the dot.
"Never Late" Early, they call me.

238
00:12:44,396 --> 00:12:46,364
No more stale jokes.

239
00:12:46,565 --> 00:12:48,157
And don't be so scared of him.

240
00:12:48,367 --> 00:12:49,994
Who's scared?

241
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:57,036
Good evening, J.L.

242
00:12:57,243 --> 00:12:59,473
- Evening.
- Father.

243
00:12:59,678 --> 00:13:02,044
Well, right on the dot.
"Never Late" Early, they call me.

244
00:13:02,248 --> 00:13:03,476
Henry.

245
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:09,548
Hi.

246
00:13:16,896 --> 00:13:18,693
Evening, Father.

247
00:13:19,498 --> 00:13:21,489
Don't scold me. I'm on time.

248
00:13:23,369 --> 00:13:25,564
- Good evening, Mrs. Winslow.
- Good evening.

249
00:13:25,771 --> 00:13:27,762
- Mr. Winslow.
- Good evening, Johnson.

250
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:31,708
- J.L.'s in the study.
- Oh, thank you, Johnson.

251
00:13:42,354 --> 00:13:45,380
You may not be the smartest, Arthur,
but you're the best-Iooking.

252
00:13:45,591 --> 00:13:47,252
Thank you!

253
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:57,194
- Good evening, Father.
- Evening.

254
00:13:57,403 --> 00:14:00,338
J.L. Evening.

255
00:14:06,378 --> 00:14:08,903
- Good evening, Johnson.
- Good evening, Miss Margaret.

256
00:14:09,114 --> 00:14:11,582
J.L. Is in the study.
Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

257
00:14:11,784 --> 00:14:13,183
Dan.

258
00:14:33,572 --> 00:14:37,474
- Hello, Dan, I see you made it.
- Oh, she went to the whip on me. Hi.

259
00:14:37,676 --> 00:14:38,973
- Father.
- J.L.

260
00:14:39,178 --> 00:14:40,702
- We're late.
- Well, that's my fault.

261
00:14:40,913 --> 00:14:42,744
There was sort of a hassle
down at the box factory.

262
00:14:42,948 --> 00:14:44,176
You see, we had this big box...

263
00:14:44,383 --> 00:14:47,113
- We'll get started.
- We...

264
00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:54,388
- How do I get out of this box?
- Leave Higginsville.

265
00:14:54,593 --> 00:14:57,289
Still in there punching, aren't you?
What's on the agenda for this evening?

266
00:14:57,496 --> 00:14:59,862
Oh, soup, cold lamb
and the financial report.

267
00:15:00,065 --> 00:15:03,262
Sounds exciting.
Say, would there be such a thing as

268
00:15:03,469 --> 00:15:05,994
- a slug of whiskey around the house?
- In this house?

269
00:15:06,205 --> 00:15:08,230
Isn't anything ever changed
around this mausoleum?

270
00:15:08,440 --> 00:15:12,069
- Yeah, bedspreads and underwear.
- The daily double.

271
00:15:23,489 --> 00:15:25,889
Any of you got ulcers yet?

272
00:15:29,528 --> 00:15:30,893
Well, here's hoping.

273
00:15:42,741 --> 00:15:46,802
The purpose of this meeting is to elect
him permanent member of this board.

274
00:15:47,012 --> 00:15:50,243
Now that he's to become
a permanent member of this family.

275
00:15:52,685 --> 00:15:55,381
But first, some good news.

276
00:16:00,926 --> 00:16:04,293
Acme Lumber Company.
Bought it today at our own figure.

277
00:16:04,930 --> 00:16:09,594
- Very good, J.L. Very good, J.L.
- Fine, fine, J.L. Fine. Fine. Fine.

278
00:16:09,902 --> 00:16:13,702
10:05 this morning, it became the
Higgins Lumber Company. Approved?

279
00:16:13,906 --> 00:16:17,899
- Why, of course, J.L. Splendid!
- Seems like a wise move, J.L.

280
00:16:18,744 --> 00:16:20,735
- You approve?
- Huh?

281
00:16:20,946 --> 00:16:24,473
Oh, naturally, J.L. Top-hole, J.L.
Of course, J.L.

282
00:16:28,487 --> 00:16:30,478
Present has no active head.

283
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:36,455
It shall remain so.

284
00:16:37,229 --> 00:16:38,958
Courage, men.

285
00:16:42,234 --> 00:16:44,668
It'll remain so until empty chair
is suitably occupied.

286
00:16:47,673 --> 00:16:49,436
If you mean me, Dad,
you're wasting your time.

287
00:16:49,641 --> 00:16:51,632
- What's that?
- You might as well forget it.

288
00:16:51,844 --> 00:16:54,074
The man I marry won't care
for the lumber business.

289
00:16:55,280 --> 00:16:57,805
- Don't be impudent, Alice.
- I'm sorry.

290
00:16:58,017 --> 00:17:00,247
That's OK, J.L.
You're still batting...

291
00:17:00,452 --> 00:17:02,511
...750.
- Maybe only 500.

292
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:05,853
Dinner.

293
00:17:22,641 --> 00:17:26,133
Meeting's opened.
Higgins Enterprise is doing fine,

294
00:17:26,345 --> 00:17:29,246
except the Higgins
Paper Box Company.

295
00:17:31,150 --> 00:17:32,879
Sales, way below normal.

296
00:17:33,385 --> 00:17:37,344
Higgins Special, nationally known,
off 22 percent.

297
00:17:37,556 --> 00:17:41,424
- Mr. Brooks, any explanation?
- Maybe paper bags are catching on.

298
00:17:44,363 --> 00:17:45,853
Could be.

299
00:17:46,065 --> 00:17:48,192
Maybe it's off gallivanting
with a ridiculous horse.

300
00:17:48,400 --> 00:17:49,628
Father!

301
00:17:50,035 --> 00:17:52,094
Let's get back to
the paper boxes, huh?

302
00:17:52,304 --> 00:17:54,329
Yes, indeed, let's.

303
00:17:54,940 --> 00:17:58,205
You came to this town
over a year ago. Penniless,

304
00:17:58,410 --> 00:18:02,244
questionable background.
Racetrack profession, I believe.

305
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:04,841
"Reformed gypsy", you said.

306
00:18:05,551 --> 00:18:07,451
You and Margaret wanted
to get married.

307
00:18:07,653 --> 00:18:09,143
I was not impressed.

308
00:18:09,354 --> 00:18:11,413
I got mine the hard way.

309
00:18:15,027 --> 00:18:16,392
Ulcers.

310
00:18:16,662 --> 00:18:19,654
But we decided upon
a probationary period.

311
00:18:19,865 --> 00:18:22,993
I put you at the head of
the Higgins Paper Box Company,

312
00:18:23,202 --> 00:18:25,227
the most successful
of the Higgins Enterprises.

313
00:18:25,571 --> 00:18:27,937
You accepted, with gratitude.

314
00:18:28,140 --> 00:18:30,131
You were the envy of Mr. Winslow
and Mr. Early.

315
00:18:30,342 --> 00:18:32,640
- Oh, no, J.L.
- No, J.L., no.

316
00:18:33,579 --> 00:18:38,016
It isn't paper bags,
my reformed gypsy friend, it's neglect.

317
00:18:38,784 --> 00:18:40,581
Shameful neglect.

318
00:18:40,786 --> 00:18:43,880
Now, Margaret's divorce, final.

319
00:18:44,089 --> 00:18:46,853
Wedding, set. Expensive.

320
00:18:47,059 --> 00:18:51,462
Four daughters, no sons.
Have to accept what they bring in.

321
00:18:51,663 --> 00:18:53,028
But I don't want to go through

322
00:18:53,232 --> 00:18:56,099
what I had to go through with the last
fellow who sat in that chair.

323
00:18:56,835 --> 00:19:00,134
- A hockey player, I believe.
- Thank you, Father.

324
00:19:00,606 --> 00:19:03,131
Beginning tomorrow,
exclusively paper boxes.

325
00:19:03,342 --> 00:19:05,276
Beginning tomorrow,
get rid of that horse.

326
00:19:07,546 --> 00:19:09,138
See that it's done.

327
00:19:09,348 --> 00:19:12,613
Now, back to Acme Lumber Company.

328
00:19:12,818 --> 00:19:14,342
I've had their statement gone
over thoroughly.

329
00:19:14,553 --> 00:19:17,818
I find a book value of
17 dollars a share.

330
00:19:18,023 --> 00:19:20,958
This allows for depreciation
in current year's taxes.

331
00:19:21,160 --> 00:19:24,493
Figures follow.
Cash on hand in banks: $13,764...

332
00:19:24,696 --> 00:19:27,096
Wait a minute!
Wait a minute, J.L. Wait here.

333
00:19:27,299 --> 00:19:30,598
You may be interested to hear I have
no intention of disposing of that horse.

334
00:19:30,802 --> 00:19:32,429
Matter of fact, I'm leaving
Higginsville in the morning.

335
00:19:32,638 --> 00:19:34,833
- Hooray! Hooray!
- Alice!

336
00:19:35,107 --> 00:19:38,008
Everything you said is true.
I have neglected the business.

337
00:19:38,377 --> 00:19:41,073
It isn't that I don't appreciate what
you've done for me. It's just that...

338
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:43,077
...I'm not built for it, that's all.

339
00:19:43,282 --> 00:19:46,217
Take handsome here. He was meant
to spend his life in an ironworks.

340
00:19:46,418 --> 00:19:49,410
And Never Late Early.
He even looks like a lampshade.

341
00:19:49,621 --> 00:19:52,852
But me, boy, I have nothing
in common with paper boxes.

342
00:19:53,992 --> 00:19:55,619
Yes, I've...

343
00:19:55,961 --> 00:19:58,122
I took it for a year, on probation.

344
00:19:58,330 --> 00:20:01,493
Isn't that beautiful, probation?
Like a criminal. What was my crime?

345
00:20:01,700 --> 00:20:05,136
I fell in love with your daughter,
so I get a year in a paper-box factory,

346
00:20:05,337 --> 00:20:07,965
where, since 1889, the Higgins
Enterprises have made a paper box

347
00:20:08,173 --> 00:20:09,731
for 4 cents and sold it for 5.

348
00:20:10,576 --> 00:20:13,272
If only once we could have made
it for 5 and sold it for 4.

349
00:20:13,478 --> 00:20:15,207
That would've been
a welcome switch.

350
00:20:15,514 --> 00:20:17,311
I know I sound crazy to you.
Maybe I am.

351
00:20:17,516 --> 00:20:18,881
Maybe you strike me the same way.

352
00:20:19,184 --> 00:20:21,277
It's just that you're only interested
in one thing:

353
00:20:21,486 --> 00:20:23,818
Accumulating wealth and gobbling up
the little fellow, like this morning

354
00:20:24,022 --> 00:20:26,354
when you snatched the Acme Lumber
Company from some poor little Joe

355
00:20:26,558 --> 00:20:29,083
who spent his lifetime building it up.
I hope it made you happy.

356
00:20:29,294 --> 00:20:30,556
- Young man! Don't...
- Look at you!

357
00:20:30,762 --> 00:20:33,322
Look at you! You haven't had
a vacation in over 40 years.

358
00:20:33,532 --> 00:20:35,932
You're just rotting away here
in this little kingdom of yours!

359
00:20:36,134 --> 00:20:39,228
Well, that's not my idea of a way
to live, and it isn't Margaret's either.

360
00:20:39,438 --> 00:20:41,065
And another thing,
I wouldn't get rid of that racehorse

361
00:20:41,273 --> 00:20:42,900
for you or anybody else in the world!

362
00:20:43,108 --> 00:20:45,599
You wait! Someday you're gonna
take off your hat to Broadway Bill.

363
00:20:46,745 --> 00:20:50,306
That's true. I was broke when I came,
and I'm going to leave the same way.

364
00:20:50,515 --> 00:20:52,380
I'm turning back every dime
of the Higgins money.

365
00:20:52,584 --> 00:20:54,142
Margaret and I'll make good
in our own way.

366
00:20:54,353 --> 00:20:56,287
We'll get married in some nice,
little church like decent people.

367
00:20:56,488 --> 00:20:58,388
If it's all the same to you,
you can accept my two weeks' notice

368
00:20:58,590 --> 00:21:01,024
two weeks ahead of time.
Margaret, I'll wait for you in the car.

369
00:21:01,226 --> 00:21:02,488
Dan!

370
00:21:02,694 --> 00:21:04,286
Let's get on with the meeting, Father.

371
00:21:04,496 --> 00:21:07,294
Darling, you come back and sit down
and behave yourself.

372
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:11,759
Margaret, this is what I wanted
to talk to you about tonight.

373
00:21:11,970 --> 00:21:14,666
Come on. Let's get out of this prison,
honey. It's fun to be free. You'll love it!

374
00:21:14,873 --> 00:21:17,137
And Broadway Bill just isn't any horse.
He's a stakes winner.

375
00:21:17,342 --> 00:21:19,537
He's got speed and stamina,
and he'll stay.

376
00:21:19,745 --> 00:21:21,576
A man waits a lifetime
for such a horse, Margaret.

377
00:21:21,780 --> 00:21:23,042
All right, all right.

378
00:21:23,248 --> 00:21:25,682
But the invitations are out,
2,000 of them.

379
00:21:25,884 --> 00:21:28,512
- Do you want to ruin it all?
- Let's get married right away, tonight.

380
00:21:28,720 --> 00:21:31,245
If I sit down in this chair again, I'm
gonna wind up just like those two guys.

381
00:21:31,456 --> 00:21:33,981
A Christmas tiger.
"Yes, J.L. Yes, J.L."

382
00:21:34,192 --> 00:21:36,820
I can't handle it.
I'll be at the apartment, packing.

383
00:21:38,230 --> 00:21:41,461
- Go with him, Margaret. Go with him!
- Oh, shut up!

384
00:21:41,833 --> 00:21:45,132
Well, Emperor Higgins,
I hope you had fun.

385
00:21:45,704 --> 00:21:47,433
Meeting is adjourned.

386
00:21:48,607 --> 00:21:52,373
<i>All a millionaire's money</i>

387
00:21:52,577 --> 00:21:56,809
<i>Couldrt build a better abode</i>

388
00:21:57,015 --> 00:21:59,779
<i>Than that someplace</i>

389
00:21:59,985 --> 00:22:04,786
<i>On Anywhere Road</i>

390
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:06,548
You might have
something there at that.

391
00:22:06,758 --> 00:22:10,125
Oh, yes, boss. Come on, perk up.

392
00:22:10,329 --> 00:22:14,561
<i>My new address will be someplace</i>

393
00:22:14,966 --> 00:22:17,025
<i>On Anywhere Road</i>

394
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:22,307
<i>It's the prettiest someplace</i>

395
00:22:22,507 --> 00:22:24,441
<i>On Anywhere Road</i>

396
00:22:24,643 --> 00:22:27,043
<i>Anywhere Road</i>

397
00:22:27,245 --> 00:22:32,182
<i>Got the fanciest rooftop</i>
<i>Made of sky</i>

398
00:22:34,653 --> 00:22:39,317
<i>Independently lucky am I</i>

399
00:22:40,125 --> 00:22:42,286
- <i>Don't need a nickel</i>
- <i>Don't need a nickel</i>

400
00:22:42,494 --> 00:22:45,691
<i>I feel at home when I'm someplace</i>

401
00:22:45,897 --> 00:22:47,660
<i>On Anywhere Road</i>

402
00:22:47,866 --> 00:22:50,198
- <i>Heading for nowhere</i>
- Yes!

403
00:22:50,402 --> 00:22:54,498
<i>Living up to the vagabond code</i>

404
00:22:58,210 --> 00:23:00,701
<i>And all a millionaire's money</i>

405
00:23:01,146 --> 00:23:04,582
<i>Couldrt build a better abode</i>

406
00:23:04,783 --> 00:23:10,585
<i>Than my someplace</i>
<i>On Anywhere Road</i>

407
00:23:20,532 --> 00:23:22,557
Programs, programs.

408
00:23:22,768 --> 00:23:24,736
What does the star mean in front
of the horse's name?

409
00:23:24,936 --> 00:23:28,633
I don't know, kid. I think the trainer's
got a boy in the service, probably.

410
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:30,740
I don't know.

411
00:23:36,782 --> 00:23:38,272
Park him and go over to see
the racing secretary.

412
00:23:38,483 --> 00:23:39,780
Yes, sir.

413
00:23:39,985 --> 00:23:42,613
- Hey, buddy, what's going on?
- They're unloading Gallant Lady!

414
00:23:42,821 --> 00:23:45,051
Gallant Lady! Oh, this I gotta see!

415
00:23:45,257 --> 00:23:48,784
Hey, Bill, here's that great champion
you're going to trim.

416
00:23:51,329 --> 00:23:52,694
Hey, Bradshaw!
Bradshaw, come here!

417
00:23:52,898 --> 00:23:54,763
- Yes, Mr. Whitehall.
- Get all these people out of the way.

418
00:23:56,268 --> 00:23:58,828
- And where do you think you're going?
- Don't race your motor, Mike.

419
00:23:59,037 --> 00:24:00,902
Never mind, Mike. Pat's the name.
Get back.

420
00:24:01,106 --> 00:24:03,631
Pat, let me see this horse.

421
00:24:03,842 --> 00:24:05,070
Now, look here, you blighters.

422
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:07,837
I'm not going to bring Gallant Lady
out before a rabble like this.

423
00:24:08,046 --> 00:24:11,015
She's not used to it. She's too nervous.
Get off the platform, will you?

424
00:24:11,216 --> 00:24:13,514
You hear what the man said?
Now get back and take it easy, will you?

425
00:24:13,718 --> 00:24:16,778
- Officer, discharge your duty!
- Aw, shut up, you foreigner.

426
00:24:20,325 --> 00:24:22,452
- All clear, Mr. Whitehall.
- Oh, all clear, eh?

427
00:24:22,661 --> 00:24:25,152
Good. All right, get her out of here.
Bring that pony out first.

428
00:24:26,731 --> 00:24:28,392
All right, bring her out.

429
00:24:29,668 --> 00:24:32,501
Keep her head down. Watch
her feet and look at her hips.

430
00:24:33,572 --> 00:24:36,166
- That's a good-Iooking filly, isn't she?
- Certainly is.

431
00:24:36,475 --> 00:24:38,170
Don't crowd her.

432
00:24:40,579 --> 00:24:43,412
Well, hello.
Win, Place and Show, huh?

433
00:24:43,615 --> 00:24:45,947
How are you, Mr. Howard?
Dan Brooks, you remember me?

434
00:24:46,151 --> 00:24:48,016
Yeah, sure. That your outfit?

435
00:24:48,220 --> 00:24:50,950
That's the transportation department
of the Dan Brooks Stable.

436
00:24:51,156 --> 00:24:53,590
- What are you hauling today?
- The winner of the Imperial Derby.

437
00:24:53,792 --> 00:24:55,316
- So? Want a tip?
- Sure. What?

438
00:24:55,527 --> 00:24:57,119
Enter the truck instead.

439
00:24:57,329 --> 00:25:00,196
- Who's getting your action?
- I only bet on sure things.

440
00:25:00,398 --> 00:25:03,458
- Gallant Lady.
- Oh, isn't that too bad?

441
00:25:03,668 --> 00:25:07,365
Gallant Lady's going to be seeing
a lot of that come derby day.

442
00:25:10,575 --> 00:25:13,840
- I thought we were betting on Sun Up.
- Why don't you broadcast it.

443
00:25:17,015 --> 00:25:19,245
- There you are.
- OK. All made out, huh?

444
00:25:19,451 --> 00:25:21,419
"Broadway Bill by Burning Ginger,
out of Mary D."

445
00:25:21,620 --> 00:25:22,848
Well, at least he's bred for speed.

446
00:25:23,054 --> 00:25:25,318
- Oh, he can scamper.
- Now, Dan, you'll have to supply

447
00:25:25,524 --> 00:25:27,719
three photos of his "night eyes"
for the Protective Bureau.

448
00:25:27,926 --> 00:25:29,450
You mean the little wart
inside the hock?

449
00:25:29,661 --> 00:25:31,754
Yes, it's a new gag.
That's different on all horses,

450
00:25:31,963 --> 00:25:33,794
- like fingerprints on a human.
- Very tricky.

451
00:25:33,999 --> 00:25:36,024
- Here's your condition book.
- Yes, sir.

452
00:25:36,234 --> 00:25:38,168
Here are your owners' badges.

453
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:40,770
Say, what's this about your wanting
to enter him in the Imperial Derby?

454
00:25:40,972 --> 00:25:43,634
Why, sure!
We're gonna come back in style, boy!

455
00:25:43,842 --> 00:25:45,537
Don't be a sucker, Dan.

456
00:25:45,744 --> 00:25:47,507
You don't think he'd beat the champ,
Gallant Lady, do you?

457
00:25:47,712 --> 00:25:50,078
What do you mean? He'll pull a spring
wagon and tie that old mare in a knot.

458
00:25:50,282 --> 00:25:51,510
Come on, what's the entry fee?

459
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:53,946
- I gotta get out of here.
- OK, all right, you win.

460
00:25:54,152 --> 00:25:57,019
It looks like you wrapped all your horse
sense in one of those paper boxes.

461
00:25:57,222 --> 00:25:58,883
Make out the stake blank.
It's $500.

462
00:26:00,258 --> 00:26:02,123
Five hundred dollars?

463
00:26:03,161 --> 00:26:06,255
Well, it's a $25,000 race.
I guess 500 is a fair fee.

464
00:26:06,464 --> 00:26:08,091
- Wouldrt you think, Mr. White?
- Peanuts.

465
00:26:08,300 --> 00:26:10,325
You want to make out
a check right now, Dan?

466
00:26:10,535 --> 00:26:13,561
- Now? Right...? Right now?
- Well, you don't have to.

467
00:26:13,772 --> 00:26:16,673
You can do it the day before the race.
Two weeks off, if you like.

468
00:26:16,875 --> 00:26:18,843
- I like.
- I thought you would.

469
00:26:19,044 --> 00:26:21,774
But you'll have to nominate him
before 6 tonight. This is the last day.

470
00:26:21,980 --> 00:26:24,312
I've got the nominating fee right here.
Yes, sir, $25, huh?

471
00:26:24,516 --> 00:26:27,110
- Fifty dollars now, Dan.
- Fifty?

472
00:26:27,319 --> 00:26:28,980
Things have gone up
in the last couple of years.

473
00:26:29,187 --> 00:26:32,247
Say, Collins, how come
4 extra pounds on my horse?

474
00:26:32,457 --> 00:26:33,822
What do you wanna do,
break him down?

475
00:26:34,025 --> 00:26:35,959
He won his last two, didn't he?
You wanna win them all?

476
00:26:36,161 --> 00:26:38,026
And another thing.
I'm not going to enter another horse

477
00:26:38,229 --> 00:26:40,220
until you loosen up that track,
Mr. Pencil-Pusher.

478
00:26:40,432 --> 00:26:41,660
If you didn't have blind staggers,

479
00:26:41,866 --> 00:26:43,800
you could look out and see them
harrowing the track right now.

480
00:26:44,002 --> 00:26:45,264
And don't call me "Pencil-Pusher".

481
00:26:45,470 --> 00:26:47,335
I'll go to Santa Anita,
where I'll get a break.

482
00:26:47,539 --> 00:26:50,770
You can go to... Oh, nothing but beefs.
Now, where are we, Dan?

483
00:26:51,376 --> 00:26:53,435
I'm up to 43. Oh...

484
00:26:54,245 --> 00:26:55,542
Mad money. Forty-four.

485
00:26:55,747 --> 00:26:57,977
I have 44.
Forty-four, 44, 44, we need 50.

486
00:26:58,183 --> 00:27:00,583
Oh, ho, Whitey, let me hear
from you. I have 44, need 50.

487
00:27:00,785 --> 00:27:03,413
Sure would surprise me.
You take a look in the vault.

488
00:27:03,622 --> 00:27:08,082
Well, the ootbay national ankbay.
Let's see what we have here.

489
00:27:09,361 --> 00:27:11,989
Bless my soul, who would have
thought that was in there?

490
00:27:12,197 --> 00:27:13,994
- Came a little hard, didn't it?
- Yes, sir.

491
00:27:14,199 --> 00:27:16,963
A Ionely, lovely little <i>finif.</i>
Thank you, brother White.

492
00:27:17,168 --> 00:27:19,568
We have 49, need 50. Have 49,
need 50. We have 49, need 50.

493
00:27:19,771 --> 00:27:21,261
Oh, ho, we have 49, need 50.
Have 49...

494
00:27:21,473 --> 00:27:23,134
- Fifty!
- Thank you, sir.

495
00:27:23,341 --> 00:27:25,536
You are a gentleman. If you're
ever down in Bourbon County,

496
00:27:25,744 --> 00:27:28,645
the smokehouse's full of hog meat,
and we got juleps 9 feet tall.

497
00:27:28,847 --> 00:27:30,405
I guess we're all nuts!

498
00:27:30,615 --> 00:27:33,140
But if this ever gets around,
I'll run you right off this track.

499
00:27:33,351 --> 00:27:35,979
Oh, nix cracken, Jimmy Bracken,
I'm as silent as the tomb.

500
00:27:36,187 --> 00:27:37,484
- There you are.
- Thank you.

501
00:27:37,689 --> 00:27:40,681
- Now we'll have to have a stall.
- Stall. Now you got me.

502
00:27:40,892 --> 00:27:42,257
Not a stall left on the track.

503
00:27:42,460 --> 00:27:43,859
What do you want me to do,
tie up under a tree?

504
00:27:44,062 --> 00:27:46,257
I was saving one
for you gypsies, but,

505
00:27:46,464 --> 00:27:49,297
well, that Gallant Lady outfit put
the bee on me for the whole shebang.

506
00:27:49,501 --> 00:27:52,629
- You know Gallant Lady, name horse.
- Oh, yeah, pulls in the public, I guess.

507
00:27:52,837 --> 00:27:54,566
Yes, she does.
Oh, wait a minute, now.

508
00:27:54,773 --> 00:27:57,708
I have got one barn. Old Pop Jones',
over here on Maple Street.

509
00:27:57,909 --> 00:27:59,877
- Not in very good shape, though.
- Oh, we don't care.

510
00:28:00,078 --> 00:28:01,875
- Broadway Bill's no snob. We'll take it.
- Good.

511
00:28:02,080 --> 00:28:03,604
And thank you, Mr. Pencil-Pusher.

512
00:28:03,815 --> 00:28:05,510
Good luck, Dan,
and don't forget those photos.

513
00:28:05,717 --> 00:28:07,241
- Oh, no, we'll have them.
- Bye, Whitey.

514
00:28:07,452 --> 00:28:09,682
Say, Collins, what are you doing,
plowing up the track?

515
00:28:09,888 --> 00:28:13,517
What is this, a corn field?
Gallant Lady won't run on a soft track.

516
00:28:13,725 --> 00:28:16,853
Now, I told you that. So help me,
I'll scratch her right out of the derby.

517
00:28:17,062 --> 00:28:18,427
Will you take it easy, Mr. Whitehall?

518
00:28:18,630 --> 00:28:20,120
That track will be lightning-fast
come derby day.

519
00:28:20,331 --> 00:28:23,027
I am doing this track a favor
by entering Gallant Lady,

520
00:28:23,234 --> 00:28:28,672
and I want a fair shake, and don't
you forget it, you pencil-pusher!

521
00:28:30,308 --> 00:28:33,175
Hey, he needs a saliva test, huh?

522
00:28:33,378 --> 00:28:38,111
- Gallant Lady. Gallant Lady.
- Oh, Gallant Lady. Oh, my dear.

523
00:28:54,933 --> 00:28:56,730
Nice and comfortable inside.

524
00:28:56,935 --> 00:28:59,267
Pretty well broke in, I guess.

525
00:29:13,885 --> 00:29:15,477
Well, I guess it's all right, Pop.

526
00:29:15,687 --> 00:29:18,952
That'll be $25 dollars a week,
in advance.

527
00:29:19,157 --> 00:29:22,183
- In advance of what?
- Well, before you move in.

528
00:29:22,393 --> 00:29:25,590
Oh, we haven't moved in yet.
A few things I want to check.

529
00:29:25,797 --> 00:29:28,425
Had some pretty fine horses
stay here.

530
00:29:28,633 --> 00:29:30,328
- Did they survive?
- Eh?

531
00:29:30,535 --> 00:29:33,129
Well, we won't quibble.
Now, who's the feed man?

532
00:29:33,338 --> 00:29:34,999
- Eh?
- The feed man. Who's the feed man?

533
00:29:35,206 --> 00:29:36,867
- Oh, the feed man.
- Yeah.

534
00:29:37,075 --> 00:29:38,303
- Right here.
- You?

535
00:29:38,510 --> 00:29:40,637
Well, now, that's a break, Whitey.
Pop's the feed man too.

536
00:29:41,346 --> 00:29:42,643
Hallelujah!

537
00:29:42,847 --> 00:29:44,474
Not too loud,
you'll wake up the termites.

538
00:29:44,682 --> 00:29:46,081
Pop, there's a few things
we're gonna need.

539
00:29:46,284 --> 00:29:50,118
We'll need some barley, some oats,
carrots, of course, and a little salt,

540
00:29:50,321 --> 00:29:52,846
- about 10 pounds of salt.
- Is this for cash?

541
00:29:53,057 --> 00:29:54,820
- Eh?
- Eh?

542
00:29:55,160 --> 00:29:58,152
- Oh, you too?
- Oh, since I was a little shaver, yeah.

543
00:29:58,363 --> 00:30:02,197
- Just this ear, though. OK here.
- I say, is this for cash?

544
00:30:02,400 --> 00:30:05,301
Cash? Now, what's the matter
with you? Don't you trust me?

545
00:30:05,503 --> 00:30:08,097
- Yeah, but I don't know you.
- Well, I don't know you.

546
00:30:08,306 --> 00:30:10,433
- But it's my barn.
- But it's my horse.

547
00:30:10,642 --> 00:30:12,667
And another thing,
we'll need some cots.

548
00:30:12,877 --> 00:30:14,504
- Eh?
- Some cots. C-O-T-S.

549
00:30:14,712 --> 00:30:17,203
- You know, to sleep on.
- You're going to sleep in here?

550
00:30:17,415 --> 00:30:19,815
Certainly! You don't think...

551
00:30:20,018 --> 00:30:23,351
Pop, that's the horse that's going
to win the Imperial Derby.

552
00:30:23,555 --> 00:30:25,648
I couldn't let him sleep
in here all by himself.

553
00:30:25,857 --> 00:30:28,985
Now, come on, Pop, get on the ball.
Wake up! Come alive!

554
00:30:29,194 --> 00:30:32,061
We're letting you in on a sure thing,
chance to pick up a bankroll.

555
00:30:32,263 --> 00:30:33,787
- This horse is a sleeper.
- He's a what?

556
00:30:33,998 --> 00:30:37,399
- He's a sleeper! A sleeper!
- You want a cot for the horse too?

557
00:30:40,939 --> 00:30:44,272
Say, he's a riot, isn't he? Pop, you're
a card. You ought to be in vaudeville.

558
00:30:44,475 --> 00:30:46,739
You're a riot!
Look, now. Come on, get on the ball.

559
00:30:46,945 --> 00:30:49,505
We gotta get some food in here for this
horse. Keep him on edge. Keep him fit.

560
00:30:49,714 --> 00:30:51,341
Get the stuff in here, now.
It's feeding time.

561
00:30:51,549 --> 00:30:53,517
Got him fit and get him ready.
Come on, move, move!

562
00:30:53,718 --> 00:30:55,083
- Whitey?
- Yes, sir, Mr. Brooks.

563
00:30:55,286 --> 00:30:57,720
Remind me to get down to the bank in
the morning and make that deposit.

564
00:30:57,922 --> 00:31:01,517
Yes, sir. It ain't safe to be carrying
that money around in your pocket.

565
00:31:01,726 --> 00:31:03,421
No, it wearies a body.

566
00:31:22,113 --> 00:31:24,240
Mr. Brooks, you certainly
got some funny ideas.

567
00:31:24,449 --> 00:31:26,178
- Why?
- When I go out to borrow money,

568
00:31:26,384 --> 00:31:28,750
I generally wear my old clothes,
my old shoes and things.

569
00:31:28,953 --> 00:31:31,615
It's plain to see you don't appreciate the
secret of the race track, then, Whitey.

570
00:31:31,823 --> 00:31:35,190
Gotta put on a front. If you look hungry
and down-at-the-mouth, you're dead.

571
00:31:35,393 --> 00:31:38,487
Now, if these threads of mine impress
Professor Pettigrew sufficiently,

572
00:31:38,696 --> 00:31:41,290
- our enforced diet is over.
- Who's Professor Pettigrew?

573
00:31:41,499 --> 00:31:44,434
Who's Professor Pettigrew? Why,
he's a gentleman, a profound scholar

574
00:31:44,636 --> 00:31:47,002
and a fellow you can bite
for a fast buck if he's got it.

575
00:31:47,205 --> 00:31:49,139
- I hope he's got it.
- Oh, he's got it, all right.

576
00:31:49,340 --> 00:31:51,365
The grapevine tells me
that the professor is literally

577
00:31:51,576 --> 00:31:53,168
infested with the green stuff.

578
00:31:53,378 --> 00:31:55,005
As a matter of fact,
he's worked out a system,

579
00:31:55,213 --> 00:31:57,238
and he's had 15 straight winners.

580
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:00,547
- Professor Pettigrew!
- Yes, angel?

581
00:32:00,752 --> 00:32:02,413
Take your feet off
my needlepoint chair!

582
00:32:02,620 --> 00:32:04,451
Yes, chicken.

583
00:32:04,656 --> 00:32:07,386
Happy, at long last, eureka!

584
00:32:07,592 --> 00:32:11,323
For 15 years, ever since I left
the faculty of Yale University,

585
00:32:11,529 --> 00:32:14,930
in utter boredom, I have been working
on the Pettigrew system

586
00:32:15,133 --> 00:32:18,125
for beating the mutuels.
And now, voilá!

587
00:32:18,770 --> 00:32:21,762
You know, he's beginning to believe
that Yale baloney himself.

588
00:32:22,106 --> 00:32:24,040
I've had my ups and downs,
but today

589
00:32:24,242 --> 00:32:26,437
I can finally say that my system
is infallible.

590
00:32:26,644 --> 00:32:30,944
It certainly is. Fifteen straight losers.
How infallible can you get?

591
00:32:31,182 --> 00:32:32,649
Is that so?

592
00:32:32,850 --> 00:32:35,284
There, Einstein. Gin.

593
00:32:35,486 --> 00:32:40,082
By an investment of a paltry $50,
I can show a profit of a $165,000

594
00:32:40,291 --> 00:32:42,759
- within two weeks!
- I read my fairy tales at night.

595
00:32:42,961 --> 00:32:45,293
But it'll cease to be a fairy tale
when I get the 50.

596
00:32:45,496 --> 00:32:47,464
Where you gonna get it,
from vinegar-puss?

597
00:32:47,799 --> 00:32:50,495
- Professor Pettigrew!
- Yes, my love.

598
00:32:50,935 --> 00:32:54,564
I'll get the 50 from the finest
gentleman that ever raced a horse:

599
00:32:54,772 --> 00:32:57,434
Dan Brooks,
a very good friend of mine.

600
00:32:57,642 --> 00:33:00,270
Anybody who had 50 bucks
wouldn't be a friend of yours.

601
00:33:00,478 --> 00:33:04,471
Is that so? Well, Dan Brooks is a
captain of industry, owns a paper mill,

602
00:33:04,682 --> 00:33:05,944
and he's never turned me down yet.

603
00:33:06,150 --> 00:33:08,778
And what's more, we're going
to be his guests at lunch today.

604
00:33:09,053 --> 00:33:12,022
- He's going to buy us lunch?
- At the Greenview Club, laddie,

605
00:33:12,223 --> 00:33:14,248
where even the busboys have
to be bank presidents.

606
00:33:14,459 --> 00:33:18,259
How do we get inside that place?
Disguised as salads?

607
00:33:18,463 --> 00:33:20,294
You overlook the power
of culture, my friend.

608
00:33:20,498 --> 00:33:21,897
I merely phoned them and said,

609
00:33:22,100 --> 00:33:24,728
"Professor Pettigrew of Yale
is lunching with Mr. Brooks,

610
00:33:24,936 --> 00:33:27,097
"the noted tycoon.
Prepare a table, please."

611
00:33:27,305 --> 00:33:29,239
Oh, by the way,
have you a dime for carfare?

612
00:33:29,440 --> 00:33:31,635
I never carry any large
denominations.

613
00:33:31,843 --> 00:33:33,538
I see. Very well, we'll walk.

614
00:33:33,745 --> 00:33:35,770
Now, the good professor's
been kind enough to invite me

615
00:33:35,980 --> 00:33:38,005
to lunch with him at
the exclusive Greenview Club,

616
00:33:38,216 --> 00:33:39,740
where the blue blood flows like water

617
00:33:39,951 --> 00:33:43,580
and the carpets are thicker
than porterhouse steaks.

618
00:33:44,389 --> 00:33:46,414
Wish me luck, huh?

619
00:33:52,096 --> 00:33:53,324
And if you can't get the money,

620
00:33:53,531 --> 00:33:57,661
bring me back a piece of that
thick carpet. Medium brown.

621
00:34:11,783 --> 00:34:13,478
- Here we are, Mr. Brooks.
- Oh, Dan.

622
00:34:13,684 --> 00:34:17,381
- Dan, my boy. Well, this is a pleasure.
- Professor.

623
00:34:17,588 --> 00:34:18,816
Capital.

624
00:34:19,023 --> 00:34:20,718
Oh, hello, hello. How are you?
Glad to see you.

625
00:34:20,925 --> 00:34:24,156
Please lower your voices.
Rule of the club.

626
00:34:24,362 --> 00:34:25,795
- I'm sorry.
- Sit down, professor.

627
00:34:25,997 --> 00:34:28,989
I took the liberty of bringing my
business associate, Oscar McGuire.

628
00:34:29,200 --> 00:34:31,532
Oscar, this is Dan Brooks.

629
00:34:31,736 --> 00:34:34,204
- How are you, sir?
- Stop me if I'm breathing too loud.

630
00:34:34,405 --> 00:34:36,236
Yeah, keep it soft,
or we'll get the heave-ho.

631
00:34:36,441 --> 00:34:38,705
This, gentlemen,
this is an occasion.

632
00:34:39,177 --> 00:34:42,544
After the separation of many years,
Damon and Pythias are reunited.

633
00:34:42,747 --> 00:34:43,975
Isn't this great?

634
00:34:44,182 --> 00:34:46,412
- Pythias.
- Damon, old pal.

635
00:34:46,617 --> 00:34:48,608
Waiter, a bottle of champagne
for auld lang syne.

636
00:34:48,820 --> 00:34:50,845
Yes, and bring a thick steak
for auld Pythias too.

637
00:34:51,055 --> 00:34:52,545
- Yes, sir.
- Bring the entire menu.

638
00:34:52,757 --> 00:34:55,248
- Fill up the table. Bring everything.
- Bring everything on.

639
00:34:55,460 --> 00:34:58,452
- And for you?
- Anything. I just came in to get warm.

640
00:34:59,630 --> 00:35:01,461
Say, your friend's pretty amusing,
isn't he?

641
00:35:01,666 --> 00:35:03,998
He comes up with some polite stuff.
Say, professor,

642
00:35:04,202 --> 00:35:06,727
- I hear you're in the upper brackets.
- <i>Comme ci, comme ca.</i>

643
00:35:06,938 --> 00:35:09,168
- <i>Parlez francais</i>, huh?
- After all, a mars wealth

644
00:35:09,373 --> 00:35:12,035
- is the friendship of those he admires.
- That's a beautiful sentiment.

645
00:35:12,243 --> 00:35:14,143
Well-put too.
But I've heard some things about you.

646
00:35:14,345 --> 00:35:16,142
I hear you've got a system,
and it's rolling.

647
00:35:16,347 --> 00:35:17,974
They tell me you're knocking
the ponies dead.

648
00:35:18,182 --> 00:35:19,615
They say that you won
more money the other day

649
00:35:19,817 --> 00:35:21,148
than you could carry away
from the race track.

650
00:35:21,519 --> 00:35:22,747
True or false?

651
00:35:23,888 --> 00:35:26,755
- Eh, how about you?
- Well, I can't complain.

652
00:35:26,958 --> 00:35:30,450
- My horse is eating.
- I...

653
00:35:33,331 --> 00:35:37,461
Modesty becomes you, Dan.
You great big industrialist.

654
00:35:38,970 --> 00:35:40,801
Wait a minute.
We'll get thrown out of here.

655
00:35:41,005 --> 00:35:42,529
You know, I always said,
"Dan Brooks.

656
00:35:42,740 --> 00:35:44,935
"There's one man that
will really come through." Eh?

657
00:35:45,143 --> 00:35:47,111
Yeah, you know what I've always
said about you, professor,

658
00:35:47,311 --> 00:35:49,541
"You're a winner in my book.
A true-blue friend."

659
00:35:49,747 --> 00:35:53,274
- How long does this go on?
- We're old pals, the social...

660
00:35:53,484 --> 00:35:55,611
The bubbly has arrived.
Well, well.

661
00:35:55,820 --> 00:35:58,948
I'm delighted for this opportunity to
repay your past favors, Dan, my boy.

662
00:35:59,157 --> 00:36:01,022
Well, thank you, professor.
You're very sweet.

663
00:36:01,225 --> 00:36:04,388
- I have a little mathematical certainty.
- Yes?

664
00:36:07,131 --> 00:36:12,068
I have a little mathematical certainty
that should net us precisely $160,000.

665
00:36:12,270 --> 00:36:14,101
- Oh, yeah?
- I wouldn't let anyone in on it but you.

666
00:36:14,305 --> 00:36:15,533
Say, it sounds good.

667
00:36:15,740 --> 00:36:17,002
- A toast.
- A toast.

668
00:36:17,208 --> 00:36:19,176
A toast to the birth
of a new syndicate.

669
00:36:19,510 --> 00:36:20,738
Pettigrew and Brooks.

670
00:36:20,945 --> 00:36:24,244
Pettigrew supplies the brains.
Brooks supplies the money.

671
00:36:25,883 --> 00:36:29,284
With a start of a mere $50
and the use of a little applied calculus,

672
00:36:29,487 --> 00:36:31,114
I have a system
of parlays worked out...

673
00:36:31,322 --> 00:36:34,780
Professor. Do these flapping
old ears of mine deceive me,

674
00:36:34,992 --> 00:36:37,517
or did you come here to put
the bite on me for 50 bucks?

675
00:36:37,728 --> 00:36:39,252
Oh, nothing as vulgar as that.

676
00:36:39,463 --> 00:36:43,194
This is an investment
in the progress of science, my boy.

677
00:36:43,401 --> 00:36:46,370
Well, don't look now, professor,
but we're back in the Dark Ages.

678
00:36:46,571 --> 00:36:47,799
You mean?

679
00:36:48,005 --> 00:36:51,406
I came here to put the bite
on you for a grand.

680
00:36:57,081 --> 00:37:00,244
You mean to tell me you're broke?

681
00:37:00,451 --> 00:37:02,476
Down to the bricks.

682
00:37:03,221 --> 00:37:05,451
I beg your pardon?

683
00:37:06,857 --> 00:37:10,190
And I came here...

684
00:37:11,896 --> 00:37:14,956
- And you came here...
- I guess so.

685
00:37:18,035 --> 00:37:20,367
Well, that's the funniest...

686
00:37:20,571 --> 00:37:22,732
It's sensational.

687
00:37:22,940 --> 00:37:24,237
What's so funny about that?

688
00:37:27,411 --> 00:37:30,903
He's trying to bite me.
I'm trying to bite him.

689
00:37:31,115 --> 00:37:32,946
Nobody's got a quarter.

690
00:37:33,150 --> 00:37:35,084
Waiter, more champagne!

691
00:37:35,286 --> 00:37:38,653
Gentlemen, please, please.
You're disturbing our patrons.

692
00:37:38,856 --> 00:37:41,825
- I'm a little disturbed myself.
- Gentlemen.

693
00:37:42,026 --> 00:37:43,994
- Professor. Come in the office.
- Yes?

694
00:37:44,195 --> 00:37:47,255
What is the exact extent
of your financial embarrassment?

695
00:37:47,465 --> 00:37:48,693
The lower depths.

696
00:37:48,899 --> 00:37:50,662
Not even enough to pay
for this meal?

697
00:37:50,868 --> 00:37:54,634
Not one bubble of this
very delightful champagne.

698
00:37:54,839 --> 00:37:58,172
Well, maybe we can get
something back on the bottle, huh?

699
00:37:58,376 --> 00:38:00,071
Hey, how's your wallet?

700
00:38:00,411 --> 00:38:02,402
I don't know. I ate it yesterday.

701
00:38:04,048 --> 00:38:07,449
Well, gentlemen. We appear
to be in something of a situation.

702
00:38:07,652 --> 00:38:09,017
To the situation.

703
00:38:09,220 --> 00:38:10,448
We might as well get
to like one another.

704
00:38:10,655 --> 00:38:12,486
We're gonna be together
for at least 30 days.

705
00:38:12,790 --> 00:38:17,250
- All right, gentlemen?
- Sure. Cut up another 30 days.

706
00:38:19,830 --> 00:38:21,889
I have been mulling
the problem over in my mind.

707
00:38:22,099 --> 00:38:23,430
- Yes?
- I have come to a simple

708
00:38:23,634 --> 00:38:26,603
- but adequate conclusion.
- I know, we all drop dead.

709
00:38:26,804 --> 00:38:28,931
- Oh, not that.
- Quiet, quiet, quiet.

710
00:38:29,140 --> 00:38:31,131
- Gentlemen, just gaze about you.
- Yes?

711
00:38:31,342 --> 00:38:34,675
All we have to do is to shock the
sensibilities of this prize collection

712
00:38:34,879 --> 00:38:38,144
of stuffed shirts,
and we will be promptly ejected.

713
00:38:38,349 --> 00:38:39,646
You know, I think he's got something.

714
00:38:39,850 --> 00:38:41,841
What'll we do? Jump up and down
and slug each other with tea bags?

715
00:38:42,053 --> 00:38:45,648
No, no, no, gentlemen.
We are in our cups.

716
00:38:45,856 --> 00:38:48,586
Or as we used to say at Yale,
we are "stinko".

717
00:38:48,793 --> 00:38:51,159
You mean we are loaded?

718
00:38:51,362 --> 00:38:54,490
- We are fractured.
- Well, here we go.

719
00:38:54,699 --> 00:38:58,863
<i>We are poor little lambs</i>
<i>Who have lost our way</i>

720
00:38:59,070 --> 00:39:03,973
- Take the tenor.
- <i>Baa, baa, baa</i>

721
00:39:04,342 --> 00:39:09,507
<i>We are little black sheep</i>
<i>Who have gone astray</i>

722
00:39:09,714 --> 00:39:12,808
- Please.
- <i>Baa, baa, baa</i>

723
00:39:13,017 --> 00:39:15,110
- Gentlemen, I beg of you.
- <i>Baa, baa, baa, baa, baa, baa</i>

724
00:39:15,319 --> 00:39:22,657
<i>Gentlemen songsters off on a spree</i>
<i>Doomed from here to eternity</i>

725
00:39:22,860 --> 00:39:25,385
Any decent restaurant would
have had us in the gutter by now.

726
00:39:25,596 --> 00:39:29,088
- It's crawling with Yale men.
- Class of '82.

727
00:39:29,300 --> 00:39:31,632
This is outrageous.
How can anyone eat in this bedlam?

728
00:39:31,836 --> 00:39:34,634
Why, I understood this to be
a dignified, quiet <i>salle á manger</i>,

729
00:39:34,839 --> 00:39:37,103
not a <i>Hofbräuhaus</i>.
We are leaving. Out of the way.

730
00:39:37,308 --> 00:39:38,832
- Is anything wrong?
- Anything wrong?

731
00:39:39,043 --> 00:39:41,477
You expect us to eat
in this collegiate cacophony?

732
00:39:41,679 --> 00:39:43,840
You'll have a sharp note
from ASCAP, sir.

733
00:39:44,048 --> 00:39:45,743
Yes, but you were the ones
who begun this.

734
00:39:45,950 --> 00:39:49,078
Us? We're Harvard men.

735
00:39:50,354 --> 00:39:55,314
<i>Baa, baa, baa</i>

736
00:39:58,796 --> 00:40:00,730
Here we are.

737
00:40:01,465 --> 00:40:02,693
Give.

738
00:40:02,900 --> 00:40:05,027
- You drive a sharp bargain, my friend.
- Yes, sir.

739
00:40:05,236 --> 00:40:07,067
That's the new light type.
You'll like that.

740
00:40:07,271 --> 00:40:10,832
Yeah. Well, it ain't exactly
the size I wanted.

741
00:40:11,041 --> 00:40:13,601
What do you want for a hamburger?
A telephone pole?

742
00:40:13,811 --> 00:40:17,747
Oh, I ain't kicking,
but I should ought to have a hat or...

743
00:40:17,948 --> 00:40:19,313
Hey.

744
00:40:19,517 --> 00:40:21,815
- I'll give you a Coke for the hat.
- That's ridiculous.

745
00:40:22,019 --> 00:40:23,680
We were just served champagne
for a song.

746
00:40:23,888 --> 00:40:25,150
- Sure.
- Pie for the tie.

747
00:40:25,356 --> 00:40:27,119
Wouldrt have anything
to hang myself with.

748
00:40:27,324 --> 00:40:29,815
What's the matter with you fellows?
I thought you was hungry.

749
00:40:30,027 --> 00:40:31,892
You should ought to have
some dessert or something.

750
00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:34,564
Wait. Look these over.
We may be in for dinner tonight.

751
00:40:34,765 --> 00:40:37,325
Spats. You should ought
to see me in spats.

752
00:40:37,535 --> 00:40:39,196
I'd be a sight for sore eyes
in spats.

753
00:40:39,403 --> 00:40:41,928
Wait till this peasant
finds out about shoes.

754
00:40:42,139 --> 00:40:43,834
- Oh, I've got shoes.
- Congratulations.

755
00:40:44,041 --> 00:40:45,372
I'll give you another hamburger
for the spats.

756
00:40:45,576 --> 00:40:47,874
No, no, he's dedicating
a drive-in market this afternoon.

757
00:40:48,078 --> 00:40:49,773
- Maybe tonight. We'll see.
- OK.

758
00:40:49,980 --> 00:40:52,346
Dinner tonight for the hat,
spats and tie. Is that a deal?

759
00:40:52,550 --> 00:40:53,881
Muff off.

760
00:40:54,084 --> 00:40:56,314
We've got a little business to talk over.
Do you mind?

761
00:40:56,520 --> 00:40:58,317
Oh, sure, sure, sure.

762
00:40:58,522 --> 00:41:00,217
Say, if you've got anything
my wife can use...

763
00:41:00,424 --> 00:41:02,790
Bring her in, and we'll cut her up.

764
00:41:04,395 --> 00:41:06,522
Smart guy, huh?

765
00:41:07,164 --> 00:41:11,191
Well, little man, what now? Raising
$500 may prove to be a slight hazard.

766
00:41:11,402 --> 00:41:12,767
Professor, you've been
a disappointment.

767
00:41:12,970 --> 00:41:14,437
Don't worry, my friend.
From now on,

768
00:41:14,638 --> 00:41:17,471
my time and wisdom will be
devoted entirely to your welfare.

769
00:41:17,675 --> 00:41:20,041
- I feel sorry for you.
- Oh, is that so?

770
00:41:20,244 --> 00:41:22,940
Well, I have a brilliant idea already.
My ace in the hole.

771
00:41:23,147 --> 00:41:24,637
- Edna.
- Edna?

772
00:41:24,849 --> 00:41:27,079
A 50-to-1 shot.
You'd have to marry her first.

773
00:41:27,284 --> 00:41:28,512
Who would Edna be?

774
00:41:28,719 --> 00:41:30,983
That's the vinegar-puss landlady
at the boarding house.

775
00:41:31,188 --> 00:41:32,485
Well, why would she expect him
to marry her?

776
00:41:32,690 --> 00:41:35,818
Confidentially, Dan, I encouraged it.
An economic necessity, you know.

777
00:41:36,026 --> 00:41:37,425
- I see.
- That'll give you an idea

778
00:41:37,628 --> 00:41:38,696
- of what I've been driven to.
- "Driven to", my foot.

779
00:41:38,696 --> 00:41:40,027
- Of what I've been driven to.
- "Driven to", my foot.

780
00:41:40,231 --> 00:41:43,098
He'd rather make phony love
to that vinegar-puss than go to work.

781
00:41:43,300 --> 00:41:46,531
Trouble is, he's got a vinegar-puss
in every race track town in the country.

782
00:41:46,737 --> 00:41:49,069
It's kept me in food and lodging
for years. And you too.

783
00:41:49,273 --> 00:41:50,570
Just... Now, wait a minute.

784
00:41:50,774 --> 00:41:53,504
This vinegar-puss...
Whatever you call her.

785
00:41:53,711 --> 00:41:55,736
Do you think she might fall
for a Ford truck?

786
00:41:55,946 --> 00:41:58,813
That's what I would call
a perfect mating.

787
00:41:59,016 --> 00:42:00,449
- What's the idea, Dan?
- Well, this Ford truck,

788
00:42:00,651 --> 00:42:02,642
I don't think any used-car dealer
would have anything to do with it.

789
00:42:02,853 --> 00:42:04,286
But maybe I could get 50 bucks
for it from her.

790
00:42:04,488 --> 00:42:06,581
What's good 50 bucks
when you need 500?

791
00:42:06,790 --> 00:42:08,849
There's a maiden race tomorrow
for $1,000.

792
00:42:09,059 --> 00:42:11,050
We drop Broadway Bill in there.
We're home free.

793
00:42:11,262 --> 00:42:13,389
But I need the 50 slugs
for the jockey and for expenses.

794
00:42:13,597 --> 00:42:16,225
An inspiration, Dan. I'll make love
as I never made love before.

795
00:42:16,433 --> 00:42:20,335
Vinegar-puss will own a Ford truck if
I have to make the supreme sacrifice.

796
00:42:20,538 --> 00:42:23,371
Bravo. Let us pray such
a necessity never arises.

797
00:42:23,574 --> 00:42:25,940
A 100-to-1 shot.

798
00:42:26,477 --> 00:42:28,377
Hey, Happy.
Who do you like in the first race?

799
00:42:28,579 --> 00:42:31,207
- Drop dead.
- Thanks.

800
00:42:39,557 --> 00:42:41,286
- Is this it?
- Yes, my dear.

801
00:42:41,492 --> 00:42:43,960
Sturdy and dependable.

802
00:42:44,161 --> 00:42:46,129
- What's it supposed to be?
- Come, my beloved.

803
00:42:46,330 --> 00:42:48,560
Broadway Bill is in the third race.
Allow me.

804
00:42:48,766 --> 00:42:52,532
Oh, darling. I didn't sleep a wink
last night thinking about you.

805
00:42:52,736 --> 00:42:54,601
- You make love so beautifully.
- Yes, I know.

806
00:42:54,805 --> 00:42:57,296
But that's only the beginning, angel,
only the beginning.

807
00:43:00,444 --> 00:43:03,277
What's the matter?
They've been there for ten minutes.

808
00:43:03,480 --> 00:43:05,641
They're having trouble
with Broadway Bill.

809
00:43:06,150 --> 00:43:08,710
Looks like we need some help
with that five horse.

810
00:43:08,919 --> 00:43:10,409
Somebody get ahold of him.

811
00:43:10,621 --> 00:43:12,316
But, sugar, we've still got time.

812
00:43:12,523 --> 00:43:13,854
- Just 10 dollars.
- No.

813
00:43:14,058 --> 00:43:15,457
- But 5 dollars.
- No.

814
00:43:15,659 --> 00:43:17,718
- Well, 2 dollars.
- No.

815
00:43:17,928 --> 00:43:19,657
But, sugar, I saw him
work out this morning.

816
00:43:19,863 --> 00:43:21,626
I'm not going to bet.

817
00:43:21,832 --> 00:43:23,857
I guess she's not going to bet,
professor.

818
00:43:24,068 --> 00:43:27,504
I guess not, and I hope she gets
a worm in her Adam's apple.

819
00:43:27,705 --> 00:43:29,570
Oh, sugar.

820
00:43:41,085 --> 00:43:43,781
Where did that thing come from?

821
00:43:45,155 --> 00:43:46,782
Get behind him and load him.

822
00:43:49,360 --> 00:43:51,920
OK, Ray.
Get him up closer.

823
00:43:52,129 --> 00:43:54,893
Now, sit still on him, rider.

824
00:43:55,966 --> 00:43:57,194
Just sit still.

825
00:43:57,735 --> 00:43:59,259
I don't think he's quite ready yet,
Mr. Brooks.

826
00:43:59,470 --> 00:44:00,835
Oh, he's ready.
Sure, he's ready.

827
00:44:01,038 --> 00:44:02,835
It's just that gate's new to him,
and all those horses.

828
00:44:03,040 --> 00:44:06,373
Once they ring that bell, he'll be so far
out in front he'll feel at home again.

829
00:44:06,877 --> 00:44:10,040
- You've got a bad horse here.
- Whoa.

830
00:44:19,123 --> 00:44:20,351
Number five.

831
00:44:28,766 --> 00:44:30,324
He's half-horse and half-nuts.

832
00:44:30,801 --> 00:44:33,031
Put him on the school list
before he starts again.

833
00:44:40,544 --> 00:44:42,341
Kind of homesick, huh, pal?

834
00:44:42,813 --> 00:44:45,179
But you gotta take on
a little nourishment, you know.

835
00:44:45,382 --> 00:44:48,840
Come on, Bill, here.
It's a carrot, Bill.

836
00:44:49,053 --> 00:44:50,418
Come on, Bill.
Here. Go on.

837
00:44:52,089 --> 00:44:54,580
When he turns down carrots,
he's lost interest in everything.

838
00:44:54,792 --> 00:44:57,920
Yeah, I don't think he's going to perk
up either until that rooster comes.

839
00:44:58,128 --> 00:44:59,356
Think she's gonna send him?

840
00:44:59,563 --> 00:45:01,190
I don't know.
She hasn't even answered my letter.

841
00:45:03,367 --> 00:45:04,857
- Skeeter.
- Skeeter.

842
00:45:05,069 --> 00:45:07,196
- Skeeter.
- Skeeter.

843
00:45:07,404 --> 00:45:10,999
- Oh, princess, am I glad to see you.
- Dan, you're smothering Skeeter.

844
00:45:11,208 --> 00:45:14,575
- Oh, Skeeter, a thousand pardons.
- Hey, Bill. Look who's here.

845
00:45:14,778 --> 00:45:16,837
It's your old buddy-buddy.

846
00:45:17,047 --> 00:45:19,242
Here. Here, look here.
Look here.

847
00:45:19,450 --> 00:45:21,247
Look here.

848
00:45:25,355 --> 00:45:26,982
Ain't that beautiful?

849
00:45:27,191 --> 00:45:28,681
Hello, Bill. Hello, Whitey.

850
00:45:28,892 --> 00:45:30,291
- Good to see you.
- He's a new horse already.

851
00:45:30,494 --> 00:45:32,587
Look at him.
I was gonna call a psychiatrist.

852
00:45:32,796 --> 00:45:35,287
- Whitey, walk him a bit, will you?
- Why, sure. Come on, boy.

853
00:45:35,499 --> 00:45:37,160
Go strut your stuff.

854
00:45:37,367 --> 00:45:39,835
There he goes again.
He wants to go for a walk too.

855
00:45:40,037 --> 00:45:43,200
Get out of here.
Princess, you're a lifesaver, really.

856
00:45:43,407 --> 00:45:45,875
Isn't that a riot? Now, who'd think
those two would go for each other?

857
00:45:46,076 --> 00:45:47,873
That's the way with a horse, though.
You get him a mascot.

858
00:45:48,078 --> 00:45:50,808
He gets attached to him. You take
him away, boom, he falls apart.

859
00:45:51,014 --> 00:45:53,107
But you didn't have to bring Skeeter.
Why didn't you ship him, honey?

860
00:45:53,317 --> 00:45:55,012
I didn't know where
to paste the stamps.

861
00:45:55,219 --> 00:45:57,153
Come on, sit down here.
Bring me up to date on everything.

862
00:45:57,354 --> 00:45:59,720
- How's Margaret?
- Oh, she's all right. She's fine.

863
00:45:59,923 --> 00:46:02,084
- How's she look? Beautiful as ever?
- Yeah, more so.

864
00:46:02,292 --> 00:46:04,055
Well, come on, tell me.
When did you see her last?

865
00:46:04,261 --> 00:46:05,489
How'd she look?
What was she wearing?

866
00:46:05,696 --> 00:46:07,425
Did she have her hair
piled up in back the way I like it?

867
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:09,963
- Yes, it was up.
- Oh, I can just see her.

868
00:46:10,501 --> 00:46:13,197
- You miss her, Dan?
- Oh, miss her and how.

869
00:46:13,403 --> 00:46:15,030
Did she say anything
about coming down?

870
00:46:15,239 --> 00:46:16,467
No, not to me, she didn't.

871
00:46:16,673 --> 00:46:18,038
Well, how'd you know about
Skeeter, then?

872
00:46:18,242 --> 00:46:20,904
Well, she let me read your letter.

873
00:46:21,111 --> 00:46:22,339
She read it to me, that is.

874
00:46:22,546 --> 00:46:24,741
And she said that I should
bring Skeeter down to you.

875
00:46:24,948 --> 00:46:27,678
She did? You see. She's beginning
to weaken. I knew she would.

876
00:46:27,885 --> 00:46:30,410
I'll have her out of Higginsville quicker
than you can say, "Never Late Early".

877
00:46:30,621 --> 00:46:31,952
Give her a big kiss for me
when you get back.

878
00:46:32,156 --> 00:46:33,453
I would, but I'm not going back.

879
00:46:33,657 --> 00:46:35,818
- What? Come on, infant, you're...
- No. No, I'm not.

880
00:46:36,026 --> 00:46:39,086
- What have we here?
- It could be my purse.

881
00:46:39,296 --> 00:46:41,230
The finance company has arrived.

882
00:46:41,431 --> 00:46:43,023
- Are you my pal? True or false?
- True.

883
00:46:43,233 --> 00:46:44,723
Then you'll hold still
for a light touch, I'm sure.

884
00:46:44,935 --> 00:46:46,493
- How light?
- Let's see what you're holding here.

885
00:46:46,703 --> 00:46:50,537
Lipstick, eyebrow pencil, comb,
compact, things and...

886
00:46:50,741 --> 00:46:52,504
Oh, pay dirt.

887
00:46:52,709 --> 00:46:55,701
- I'll take this. You may have that.
- Well, that seems fair.

888
00:46:55,913 --> 00:46:57,881
With this 50, I can enter Bill
in an overnight race tomorrow.

889
00:46:58,081 --> 00:47:00,174
If he wins, I'll have 500
to put him in the big heat.

890
00:47:00,384 --> 00:47:02,113
- Oh, he'll win.
- Oh, he'll walk his beat.

891
00:47:02,319 --> 00:47:04,913
And after he wins the big one,
I'll pay you this back with interest.

892
00:47:05,122 --> 00:47:06,714
Did I save you enough
for a train fare home?

893
00:47:06,924 --> 00:47:09,358
It doesn't matter. I'm staying
at the hotel till after the race.

894
00:47:09,560 --> 00:47:10,959
- No, no.
