01:23:16,491 --> 01:23:20,222
<i>We are</i>
<i>We are</i>

1535
01:23:20,428 --> 01:23:23,761
<i>And I won't...</i>

1536
01:23:23,965 --> 01:23:27,924
Where's Bill? Hey. Hey.

1537
01:23:28,870 --> 01:23:33,239
Bill? Bill! Bill!

1538
01:23:34,542 --> 01:23:38,171
- Whitey!
- Mr. Brooks! Mr. Brooks!

1539
01:23:38,380 --> 01:23:40,678
Where's the horse? Where's Bill?
He's not in his stall.

1540
01:23:40,882 --> 01:23:42,110
- Where is he?
- They took him away.

1541
01:23:42,317 --> 01:23:43,614
- Who?
- Mr. Jones, the feed man.

1542
01:23:43,818 --> 01:23:45,376
- He came here with the sheriff.
- The sheriff?

1543
01:23:45,587 --> 01:23:47,316
- Yes, sir, and took him off.
- Why didn't you stop them?

1544
01:23:47,522 --> 01:23:49,888
I tried, but they had papers.
They put a rope around his neck

1545
01:23:50,091 --> 01:23:51,490
- A rope?
- And tied him to an automobile

1546
01:23:51,693 --> 01:23:53,058
- and dragged him off.
- Which way did they go?

1547
01:23:53,261 --> 01:23:55,388
I chased them for half a mile,
but it didn't do no good.

1548
01:23:55,597 --> 01:23:58,862
Dan! Dan, wait! Wait!

1549
01:23:59,768 --> 01:24:01,861
Get in that stall!

1550
01:24:03,171 --> 01:24:05,662
- Get in there, or I'II...
- What are you doing to that horse?

1551
01:24:05,874 --> 01:24:07,774
Why, you dirty...

1552
01:24:10,845 --> 01:24:13,678
- Hey, what's going on?
- What's going on here?

1553
01:24:13,882 --> 01:24:16,942
- Come on, let go. Break it up.
- Take it easy, now.

1554
01:24:17,152 --> 01:24:18,380
- Let go of me!
- Take it easy.

1555
01:24:18,586 --> 01:24:21,521
That rat was whipping my horse!
He was beating my horse!

1556
01:24:22,891 --> 01:24:24,688
Cool off and have a nice sleep.

1557
01:24:24,893 --> 01:24:26,690
Don't you worry about me,
you better take care of my horse.

1558
01:24:26,895 --> 01:24:28,157
I'll go right out and cut him some hay.

1559
01:24:28,363 --> 01:24:30,331
That's Broadway Bill,
he's in the Imperial Derby tomorrow.

1560
01:24:30,532 --> 01:24:32,329
He'll look funny carrying the judge
across the finish line.

1561
01:24:32,534 --> 01:24:35,765
He'll carry the judge, jury, the clerk of
the court and bailiff and win that heat.

1562
01:24:36,004 --> 01:24:37,596
- What's eating him?
- Search me.

1563
01:24:37,806 --> 01:24:40,138
Somebody attacks his nag,
and he's blowing his top.

1564
01:24:46,181 --> 01:24:47,808
What's the matter, operator?
I wanna get Pittsburgh.

1565
01:24:48,016 --> 01:24:52,453
If Detroit can't handle any more, OK.
What price? OK, 2,000 on Sun Up.

1566
01:24:52,654 --> 01:24:54,747
Denver, 2,200. Frisco, 1,800.
New Orleans, 3,000.

1567
01:24:54,956 --> 01:24:57,049
- Dallas, 12. New York, 9,000.
- What's the total? What's the total?

1568
01:24:57,258 --> 01:24:59,249
- Close to 40,000.
- Why, we haven't even started yet.

1569
01:24:59,461 --> 01:25:00,985
- What's the average?
- About 7-to-1.

1570
01:25:01,196 --> 01:25:04,461
7-to-1? Listen, Sully, I'm gonna
shoot the works on that horse of yours.

1571
01:25:04,666 --> 01:25:06,930
I hope we're not pulling a boner.
You're sure he's all right?

1572
01:25:07,135 --> 01:25:09,330
- Sun Up? If it wasrt for Gallant Lady...
- Forget Gallant Lady.

1573
01:25:09,537 --> 01:25:10,799
- He's a cinch to beat all the others.
- OK.

1574
01:25:11,439 --> 01:25:12,770
All right, folks,
get your bets down, please.

1575
01:25:12,974 --> 01:25:14,737
Don't get shut out.
The big race of the day.

1576
01:25:14,943 --> 01:25:16,342
Any bets on Broadway Bill?

1577
01:25:16,544 --> 01:25:18,512
Not one. They're laying off
of that plug like poison.

1578
01:25:18,713 --> 01:25:20,840
- Ten dollars on Sun Up to win.
- Better make him 100-to-1.

1579
01:25:21,049 --> 01:25:22,516
- Might pick up some sucker money.
- OK.

1580
01:25:22,717 --> 01:25:24,150
Make Broadway Bill 100-to-1.

1581
01:25:24,352 --> 01:25:27,651
All right, folks,
Broadway Bill is 100-to-1.

1582
01:25:28,223 --> 01:25:31,420
A 100-to-1 shot.

1583
01:25:31,626 --> 01:25:34,595
Broadway Bill, you old rascal.

1584
01:25:34,796 --> 01:25:36,229
Where have you been all my life?

1585
01:25:36,431 --> 01:25:38,092
Horses again.
You'd think they were men.

1586
01:25:38,299 --> 01:25:40,233
Here's where I give
that bookie heart failure.

1587
01:25:40,435 --> 01:25:42,801
He's going to buy my fall outfit
and doesn't know it.

1588
01:25:43,004 --> 01:25:44,835
Number 28.
That's you again, Mae.

1589
01:25:45,039 --> 01:25:48,566
Oh, it would be. That old moneybags
in 28 is going to drive me...

1590
01:25:48,776 --> 01:25:50,471
Why, Mae, you ought to be thrilled.

1591
01:25:50,678 --> 01:25:53,306
J.P. Chase is the richest man
in the world.

1592
01:25:53,681 --> 01:25:57,549
Confound it, where is everybody?
Nurse? Nurse!

1593
01:25:57,752 --> 01:26:01,381
- Now, now, what's all the excitement?
- I've gotta get out of here.

1594
01:26:01,589 --> 01:26:04,080
- You're a big boy now.
- Well, I tell you, I've got to get out of...

1595
01:26:04,292 --> 01:26:06,920
- Oh, no, now, not another needle.
- Not this time, cutie.

1596
01:26:07,128 --> 01:26:10,154
Where's that idiot of a doctor?
I'm going crazy in here.

1597
01:26:10,365 --> 01:26:12,230
Now, take it easy.
You've got a broken leg.

1598
01:26:12,433 --> 01:26:14,594
Broken leg. I've got a broken back
from lying here,

1599
01:26:14,802 --> 01:26:16,793
- reading this cheap trash.
- Relax.

1600
01:26:17,005 --> 01:26:18,336
I've got a business to attend to,
young woman.

1601
01:26:18,540 --> 01:26:21,134
Relax. So you didn't make
another million in the market today.

1602
01:26:21,342 --> 01:26:24,106
Oh, is that so?
Well, tell me something, smarty.

1603
01:26:24,312 --> 01:26:26,246
How do you pass
your time in this prison?

1604
01:26:26,447 --> 01:26:27,675
Oh, I flirt with the angels.

1605
01:26:27,882 --> 01:26:29,372
- You what?
- Bet on horses.

1606
01:26:29,584 --> 01:26:31,984
You bet on horses?
That keep your mind occupied?

1607
01:26:32,187 --> 01:26:36,556
Brother, it keeps my mind occupied,
my blood boiling and my purse empty.

1608
01:26:36,758 --> 01:26:38,487
Well, what horse
are you betting on today?

1609
01:26:38,693 --> 01:26:41,890
- Broadway Bill.
- Broadway Bill? Why?

1610
01:26:42,096 --> 01:26:45,463
It's 100-to-1. That's reason enough.
And I'm going to win one someday.

1611
01:26:45,667 --> 01:26:47,931
100-to-1?
How much money are you betting?

1612
01:26:48,136 --> 01:26:49,626
- Two smackers.
- Two what?

1613
01:26:49,837 --> 01:26:53,034
Two smackers. Dollars. Those things
you get nightmares about.

1614
01:26:53,241 --> 01:26:57,405
Oh, all right. Well, you can
bet 2 smackers for me.

1615
01:26:57,612 --> 01:27:00,706
- You?
- Well, why not, huh?

1616
01:27:00,915 --> 01:27:03,850
Give me something to think about.
One. Two. There.

1617
01:27:04,052 --> 01:27:06,020
- Boy, is this funny.
- What's funny?

1618
01:27:06,221 --> 01:27:09,247
You, the richest man in the world,
betting 2 bucks on a nag.

1619
01:27:09,457 --> 01:27:11,857
- Are you sure you can spare it?
- Go on. You get out of here.

1620
01:27:12,060 --> 01:27:14,927
Just put that 2 bucks on that
Buffalo Bill or whatever his name is.

1621
01:27:15,129 --> 01:27:16,858
This is going to rock Wall Street.

1622
01:27:17,065 --> 01:27:19,863
Just a minute, young lady.
How will I know we've won?

1623
01:27:20,368 --> 01:27:23,462
You'll know. I'll come in
and dance a hula for you.

1624
01:27:24,172 --> 01:27:26,538
Well, that's something.

1625
01:27:28,176 --> 01:27:29,803
Steve, you want to hear
something funny?

1626
01:27:30,011 --> 01:27:32,673
J.P. Chase just bet 2 whole dollars
on Broadway Bill.

1627
01:27:32,880 --> 01:27:35,110
Oh, really? That's very funny.

1628
01:27:35,316 --> 01:27:40,344
Hey, Rosie, get this. Old J.P. Chase
just bet 2 C's on Broadway Bill.

1629
01:27:41,155 --> 01:27:43,020
Broadway Bill?

1630
01:27:44,759 --> 01:27:48,889
Broadway Bill? Hey, J.P. Chase
just bet 2 G's on Broadway Bill!

1631
01:27:49,097 --> 01:27:50,928
J.P. Chase? What do
you know about that?

1632
01:27:51,132 --> 01:27:53,794
- Boy, that's good enough for me.
- Give me that phone.

1633
01:27:54,002 --> 01:27:55,936
Yeah, 20,000 bucks.
Can you imagine that?

1634
01:27:56,137 --> 01:27:58,731
J.P. Chase don't chuck it down
like that unless he knows something.

1635
01:27:58,940 --> 01:28:02,137
- Must be hot. He bet 50,000 smackers.
- A hundred thousand? You're kidding.

1636
01:28:02,343 --> 01:28:04,334
I just got it from the inside.
Two hundred grand.

1637
01:28:04,545 --> 01:28:05,773
On Broadway Bill?

1638
01:28:05,980 --> 01:28:08,005
Cross my heart. He said something
like a quarter of a million.

1639
01:28:08,216 --> 01:28:10,446
Wow! On a 100-to-1 shot too.

1640
01:28:11,219 --> 01:28:13,050
Two bucks on Broadway Bill,
on the nose.

1641
01:28:13,254 --> 01:28:14,812
Two hundred dollars to win
on Broadway Bill.

1642
01:28:15,023 --> 01:28:16,991
Give me $2 to win on
Broadway Bill for me,

1643
01:28:17,191 --> 01:28:19,091
$2 for my brother,
and $2 for my wife.

1644
01:28:19,294 --> 01:28:20,522
I got a telegram on him.

1645
01:28:20,728 --> 01:28:22,423
You ought to get a bet on him yourself.
He's gonna win!

1646
01:28:22,630 --> 01:28:24,655
It scared me to death.
I thought it was my mother.

1647
01:28:24,866 --> 01:28:28,267
Who? Broadway Bill
hasn't got a chance.

1648
01:28:28,469 --> 01:28:31,404
What do I care what a bunch of yokels
are doing? Let them bet their heads off.

1649
01:28:31,606 --> 01:28:33,506
The more they do,
the better I'm gonna like it.

1650
01:28:33,708 --> 01:28:34,936
Look what they're doing for us.

1651
01:28:35,143 --> 01:28:36,804
They sent the price of Sun Up
from 4-to-1 up to 12-to-1.

1652
01:28:37,011 --> 01:28:40,811
Boss, we've got one less horse to beat.
Broadway Bill's going to be scratched.

1653
01:28:41,015 --> 01:28:42,482
What do you mean, "scratched"?

1654
01:28:42,684 --> 01:28:45,278
- I didn't make this up, I just heard it.
- Well, what happened?

1655
01:28:45,486 --> 01:28:46,748
I thought I was bringing you
some good news.

1656
01:28:46,954 --> 01:28:48,182
All right, come on, what happened?

1657
01:28:48,389 --> 01:28:50,857
I don't know. The guy that owns him
got himself in a jam. He's in jail.

1658
01:28:51,626 --> 01:28:53,924
In jail?
With Broadway Bill out of the race,

1659
01:28:54,128 --> 01:28:55,823
the odds on Sun Up will go
right back to 4-to-1.

1660
01:28:56,064 --> 01:28:58,430
Listen, I've got to get ahold
of that guy. What's his name?

1661
01:28:58,633 --> 01:29:00,863
- Brooks. Dan Brooks.
- Brooks. Dan Brooks, that's right.

1662
01:29:01,069 --> 01:29:03,037
He's got to put Broadway Bill
back in the race.

1663
01:29:03,237 --> 01:29:05,671
Now, you fellows don't lay
any bets till I get back.

1664
01:29:06,908 --> 01:29:08,933
Company.

1665
01:29:09,677 --> 01:29:11,770
- Hello, Dan.
- Hello, Mr. Howard.

1666
01:29:11,979 --> 01:29:14,243
What's this little delegation here?

1667
01:29:14,716 --> 01:29:18,277
You fellows didn't bring
a loaf of bread with a file in it, did you?

1668
01:29:18,486 --> 01:29:20,613
I'd ask you in, only the door
seems to be stuck.

1669
01:29:20,822 --> 01:29:22,847
- What happened?
- Well, along about the third round,

1670
01:29:23,057 --> 01:29:25,787
I found out the guy I was messing with
was wearing a badge, so here I am.

1671
01:29:25,993 --> 01:29:27,620
It isn't bad, though.
It keeps me out of the pool hall.

1672
01:29:27,829 --> 01:29:29,763
What's the idea,
scratching that horse of yours?

1673
01:29:29,964 --> 01:29:31,829
It's a long, dull story.
Something about a feed bill.

1674
01:29:32,033 --> 01:29:34,661
You've got me in a mess. I've got a lot
of dough bet on that horse of yours.

1675
01:29:34,869 --> 01:29:36,097
- You have?
- Sure.

1676
01:29:36,304 --> 01:29:37,532
- Did you see him work?
- Oh, sure, sure.

1677
01:29:37,739 --> 01:29:38,967
You know, I had that horse
go a mile in...

1678
01:29:39,173 --> 01:29:41,573
Why don't you tell a guy when you're in
a jam? How much are you in hock for?

1679
01:29:41,776 --> 01:29:44,176
- Oh, about 200, I guess.
- Why, that's chicken feed.

1680
01:29:44,379 --> 01:29:46,574
Never keep a secret
like that from a pal.

1681
01:29:46,781 --> 01:29:48,009
- Here.
- What's this?

1682
01:29:48,216 --> 01:29:49,877
Go ahead, you want the horse
back in the race, don't you?

1683
01:29:50,084 --> 01:29:52,484
- Well, yeah.
- Well, so do I.

1684
01:29:53,054 --> 01:29:55,079
You're not the old man
with the whiskers, are you?

1685
01:29:55,289 --> 01:29:57,484
Never mind, I'm just grateful.
I'll pay you back soon as I can.

1686
01:29:57,692 --> 01:29:59,819
Forget it. I'll get paid back plenty
when that horse breezes in.

1687
01:30:00,027 --> 01:30:02,461
- He'll breeze in. Don't worry about that.
- You got a jockey?

1688
01:30:02,663 --> 01:30:04,460
Well, I was talking to this little boy,
Eddie Jacobs.

1689
01:30:04,665 --> 01:30:06,428
He's an apprentice.
How about Ted Williams?

1690
01:30:06,634 --> 01:30:08,124
Ted Williams? Can you get him?

1691
01:30:08,336 --> 01:30:10,827
Can I get him? He'll do
anything for me. We're like that.

1692
01:30:11,038 --> 01:30:13,563
With Williams aboard, it's just bring
a buck and a truck, and we're home.

1693
01:30:13,775 --> 01:30:16,175
Go on down to the captain.
Pay his fine. Get him out of here.

1694
01:30:16,377 --> 01:30:18,004
Put up a bond, whatever they want,
but get him out fast.

1695
01:30:18,212 --> 01:30:19,440
- OK, boss.
- Now, you're all clear.

1696
01:30:19,647 --> 01:30:22,548
I don't know how to thank you.
If you were free, I'd marry you.

1697
01:30:22,750 --> 01:30:24,479
Don't you worry,
I'll make plenty on that race.

1698
01:30:24,685 --> 01:30:26,619
I'll have Williams come up
and see you right away. So long, Dan.

1699
01:30:26,821 --> 01:30:28,049
- Oh, say, Eddie.
- Yeah?

1700
01:30:28,256 --> 01:30:30,622
Where will we go on
our honeymoon? Hey, guard.

1701
01:30:30,825 --> 01:30:34,090
Hey, princess, Whitey.
Teddy Williams, the rider.

1702
01:30:34,295 --> 01:30:36,923
- Oh, hello.
- How do you do, Mr. Williams?

1703
01:30:37,131 --> 01:30:38,633
- How do you do?
- Bill, this is D-day for you.

1704
01:30:38,633 --> 01:30:39,395
- How do you do?
- Bill, this is D-day for you.

1705
01:30:39,600 --> 01:30:43,058
And here's the boy that's gonna
ride you to glory. Ted Williams, Bill.

1706
01:30:43,271 --> 01:30:45,136
- He looks sharp.
- He's fit and ready to run.

1707
01:30:45,339 --> 01:30:48,433
I blew him out of the gate this morning.
Three-eighths of a mile in 35 flat.

1708
01:30:48,643 --> 01:30:50,668
- Thirty-five?
- Crying to run all the way.

1709
01:30:50,878 --> 01:30:52,743
How is he in the gate?
I hear he threw his last jock.

1710
01:30:52,947 --> 01:30:55,074
Oh, he's OK now.
That was only his first out, kid.

1711
01:30:55,283 --> 01:30:57,513
- Has he got a hard mouth?
- Cast iron. Don't try to hold him.

1712
01:30:57,718 --> 01:30:58,946
He doesn't like to be held.

1713
01:30:59,153 --> 01:31:02,247
You just hang on, Mr. Williams.
Old Bill will do the rest.

1714
01:31:02,457 --> 01:31:03,947
I guess I'm just going along
for the ride.

1715
01:31:04,158 --> 01:31:06,786
And ten percent of the purse. Well,
you better get over to the jocks' room.

1716
01:31:06,994 --> 01:31:08,256
Be prepared to have
your picture taken, son,

1717
01:31:08,463 --> 01:31:09,828
because you're gonna be
in the winner's circle.

1718
01:31:10,031 --> 01:31:11,760
Whitey, looks like the old man
with the whiskers

1719
01:31:11,966 --> 01:31:14,025
- has really got his arms around us?
- Yes, sir.

1720
01:31:14,235 --> 01:31:15,793
Bill, I've got a little bit
of a shock for you.

1721
01:31:16,003 --> 01:31:18,301
Havert got the truck to take
you to the race track today.

1722
01:31:18,506 --> 01:31:20,736
Old Bill, he'll walk just like
the rest of us poor people.

1723
01:31:20,942 --> 01:31:22,170
I guess so.

1724
01:31:22,376 --> 01:31:23,741
<i>Take your places</i>
<i>Off to the races</i>

1725
01:31:23,945 --> 01:31:26,470
<i>We don't give a rap</i>
<i>And we're off to the handicap</i>

1726
01:31:38,092 --> 01:31:41,550
Yeah, this joint's full of smoke.
Don't nobody ever inale?

1727
01:31:41,762 --> 01:31:43,923
Doc, will you move over
with that pipe, Hempstead?

1728
01:31:44,131 --> 01:31:45,894
You're killing me with that pipe.

1729
01:31:46,100 --> 01:31:47,965
What are you smoking, overhalls?

1730
01:31:52,640 --> 01:31:54,733
<i>The Camptown ladies sing this song</i>

1731
01:31:54,942 --> 01:31:56,876
<i>A doo-dah, a doo-dah</i>

1732
01:31:57,078 --> 01:31:59,478
<i>The Camptown race track</i>
<i>Nine miles long</i>

1733
01:31:59,680 --> 01:32:01,045
<i>Oh, doo-dah day</i>

1734
01:32:01,249 --> 01:32:03,547
<i>I came down there</i>
<i>With my hat caved in</i>

1735
01:32:03,751 --> 01:32:05,719
- <i>Doo-dah, a doo-dah</i>
- <i>A doo-dah, doo-dah</i>

1736
01:32:05,920 --> 01:32:07,979
<i>Go back home</i>
<i>With a pocket full of tin</i>

1737
01:32:08,189 --> 01:32:10,248
<i>Oh, doo-dah day</i>

1738
01:32:10,458 --> 01:32:12,619
- <i>Gwine to run all night</i>
- <i>Gwine to run all night</i>

1739
01:32:12,827 --> 01:32:14,658
- <i>Gwine to run all day</i>
- <i>Gwine to run all day</i>

1740
01:32:14,862 --> 01:32:16,955
<i>I'll bet my money</i>
<i>On the bobtailed nag</i>

1741
01:32:17,164 --> 01:32:19,064
<i>Somebody bet on the bay</i>

1742
01:32:19,267 --> 01:32:21,428
