- <i>Gwine to run all day</i>
- <i>All night, all day</i>

1765
01:33:09,183 --> 01:33:10,878
<i>I'll bet on the bobtailed nag</i>

1766
01:33:11,085 --> 01:33:14,054
<i>Oh, doo-dah day</i>

1767
01:33:14,255 --> 01:33:18,021
- <i>Oh, doo-dah day</i>
- <i>Oh, doo-dah day</i>

1768
01:33:20,061 --> 01:33:21,323
That mob down there's gone crazy.

1769
01:33:21,529 --> 01:33:23,360
You know what Broadway Bill
is at the track? 6-to-1.

1770
01:33:23,564 --> 01:33:25,088
- What are you worrying about?
- Now, listen, Eddie,

1771
01:33:25,299 --> 01:33:27,426
there's a lot of dough going down on
that horse. Where's it coming from?

1772
01:33:27,635 --> 01:33:30,035
A plug like Broadway Bill doesn't get
a play like that unless something's up.

1773
01:33:30,237 --> 01:33:31,499
Somebody knows something,
I tell you.

1774
01:33:31,706 --> 01:33:33,435
Maybe it's the Greek.
Maybe he's trying to pull a fast one.

1775
01:33:33,641 --> 01:33:35,768
- You're screwy. The Greek's in with us.
- Then where is it coming from?

1776
01:33:35,977 --> 01:33:38,639
Use your brain, maybe you'd find out.
Did you ever try to figure it out?

1777
01:33:38,846 --> 01:33:41,314
Every bet that's being placed on
Broadway Bill is a 2-buck bet.

1778
01:33:41,515 --> 01:33:43,813
Two bucks. Does that sound like
wise money to you?

1779
01:33:44,018 --> 01:33:45,986
It starts out 50-to-1,
meat for the sucker.

1780
01:33:46,187 --> 01:33:48,815
Every barber, bootblack and
chambermaid scrambles to get aboard.

1781
01:33:49,023 --> 01:33:50,650
The rumor gets started,
the first thing you know,

1782
01:33:50,858 --> 01:33:52,758
all the poor boobs are trying
to hock their undershirts.

1783
01:33:52,960 --> 01:33:54,427
I've seen it happen a million times.

1784
01:33:54,629 --> 01:33:56,221
It's sucker money, that's what it is.
Sucker money.

1785
01:33:56,430 --> 01:33:57,658
Well, I still don't like it.

1786
01:33:57,865 --> 01:34:00,197
Maybe you'd be happier if you knew that
Ted Williams was riding Broadway Bill.

1787
01:34:00,401 --> 01:34:02,164
- He is?
- Yeah, Williams on Broadway Bill,

1788
01:34:02,370 --> 01:34:04,167
and Roberts on Gallant Lady.
Now are you happy?

1789
01:34:04,372 --> 01:34:05,964
- Sun Up is 20-to-1 in Chicago.
- What did I tell you?

1790
01:34:06,173 --> 01:34:07,902
- How much will they handle?
- How much will you handle?

1791
01:34:08,109 --> 01:34:09,337
- Fifteen thousand?
- OK.

1792
01:34:09,543 --> 01:34:10,976
- New York, 20-to-1.
- How much can they handle?

1793
01:34:11,178 --> 01:34:12,770
How much can you handle?
About 20.

1794
01:34:12,980 --> 01:34:16,416
OK. Chicago, 15 grand.
New York, 20 grand.

1795
01:34:17,518 --> 01:34:18,849
You want the race run honestly,
don't you?

1796
01:34:19,053 --> 01:34:21,521
Naturally, but I don't like
this implication that my jockey...

1797
01:34:21,722 --> 01:34:23,883
Listen, Mr. Whitehall,
we spend a fortune every year

1798
01:34:24,091 --> 01:34:28,118
maintaining our Protective Bureau.
Why? To try to keep racing honest.

1799
01:34:28,329 --> 01:34:29,921
If we can't have it that way,
we'll close the track up.

1800
01:34:30,131 --> 01:34:32,929
Yes, I know, but what makes you think
that my boy is involved?

1801
01:34:33,134 --> 01:34:35,398
I had Howard trailed,
and I had his men trailed.

1802
01:34:35,603 --> 01:34:38,094
I was determined to find out
just what he had up his sleeve,

1803
01:34:38,305 --> 01:34:41,638
and I found out, Mr. Whitehall.
Your jockey, Roberts.

1804
01:34:42,777 --> 01:34:45,007
Well, that's the works.
How much have we got down?

1805
01:34:45,212 --> 01:34:47,442
A hundred and one thousand,
average 12-to-1.

1806
01:34:47,648 --> 01:34:50,242
Over a million bucks.
It's the one we've been waiting for.

1807
01:34:51,252 --> 01:34:53,345
Hey, boss, did you hear
what happened?

1808
01:34:53,554 --> 01:34:57,012
Joey Roberts has been suspended.
He ain't gonna ride Gallant Lady.

1809
01:34:57,224 --> 01:34:58,851
- How did you find that out?
- I saw it on the bulletin.

1810
01:34:59,060 --> 01:35:01,187
They got Bobby North aboard.

1811
01:35:01,395 --> 01:35:03,829
Somebody smelled a rat.
This is a mess. Come on.

1812
01:35:04,031 --> 01:35:06,556
I knew this was too good to be true.

1813
01:35:07,301 --> 01:35:09,030
<i>The horses are now in the paddock.</i>

1814
01:35:25,319 --> 01:35:28,482
I'm only interested in one horse.
Sun Up, number five.

1815
01:35:28,689 --> 01:35:30,418
Beat him and you win this race.

1816
01:35:30,624 --> 01:35:32,216
You're up against some
tough customers.

1817
01:35:32,426 --> 01:35:34,189
That jockey on Sun Up
might try anything.

1818
01:35:34,395 --> 01:35:37,125
Don't let him get away with it.
Gallant Lady must win this race.

1819
01:35:37,331 --> 01:35:40,266
Now, there's only one horse
you've got to beat. It's Gallant Lady.

1820
01:35:40,468 --> 01:35:42,561
But you've got to beat her.
I don't care how.

1821
01:35:42,770 --> 01:35:44,328
You've ridden lots of races and won.

1822
01:35:44,538 --> 01:35:47,132
If you win this, there's a 5 G bonus
for you, if you do.

1823
01:35:47,641 --> 01:35:51,008
Use your head or anything else
that's necessary,

1824
01:35:51,212 --> 01:35:53,009
but you've got to beat Gallant Lady.
Understand?

1825
01:35:53,280 --> 01:35:55,680
Listen, son. Bill don't like to run in
behind horses. See?

1826
01:35:55,883 --> 01:35:58,443
If you get boxed or pocketed,
take him back and go around.

1827
01:35:58,652 --> 01:36:00,677
Don't worry if you lose a little ground.
He'll make it up for you.

1828
01:36:00,888 --> 01:36:03,550
There's one thing, though.
You've got to remember this one thing.

1829
01:36:03,758 --> 01:36:05,248
- Are you listening to me?
- Yeah, sure.

1830
01:36:05,459 --> 01:36:07,120
This is a free-running horse, see.
Don't hold him back.

1831
01:36:07,328 --> 01:36:10,525
Give him his head.
Give him his head, or he'll go crazy.

1832
01:36:10,731 --> 01:36:12,665
I got to win this race, son.
I got to.

1833
01:36:12,867 --> 01:36:15,768
I don't want to give you the house-and-
mortgage or the sick-mother routine,

1834
01:36:15,970 --> 01:36:17,938
but my whole future depends on it.

1835
01:36:18,139 --> 01:36:19,834
I can't explain, but that's it.

1836
01:36:20,174 --> 01:36:22,233
- Good luck to you.
- Good luck to you.

1837
01:36:22,977 --> 01:36:24,638
Jockeys up.

1838
01:36:27,815 --> 01:36:29,806
Now, remember, it's up to you.

1839
01:36:30,017 --> 01:36:33,077
If you're smart, you'll cop this race.
Remember, it's up to you.

1840
01:36:33,387 --> 01:36:36,151
Well, Bill, it's up to you, boy.

1841
01:36:39,026 --> 01:36:40,357
Must be nervous.
What are you shaking for?

1842
01:36:40,561 --> 01:36:41,789
Who's shaking?

1843
01:36:49,336 --> 01:36:52,328
Come on, Skeeter,
let's go see a good race. Come on.

1844
01:37:07,721 --> 01:37:10,212
<i>The horses are on the track.</i>

1845
01:37:10,791 --> 01:37:12,156
Here he comes.

1846
01:37:19,400 --> 01:37:20,833
- Dan.
- Well, it won't be long now.

1847
01:37:21,035 --> 01:37:23,560
Dan, Dan, I stand
at the crossroads of destiny.

1848
01:37:23,771 --> 01:37:25,500
If we don't win,
it's goodbye, professor.

1849
01:37:25,706 --> 01:37:27,970
- Why, what's the matter?
- I got 50 from Edna this morning,

1850
01:37:28,175 --> 01:37:31,110
but I had to promise to marry her
if Broadway Bill loses.

1851
01:37:31,312 --> 01:37:32,836
Well, a fellow can always
change his mind.

1852
01:37:33,047 --> 01:37:35,345
Not with vinegar-puss.
She made him put it in writing.

1853
01:37:35,549 --> 01:37:38,848
Confidentially, Dan, it can't be done.
I'm slightly married already.

1854
01:37:39,153 --> 01:37:41,747
- Well, who to?
- To another vinegar-puss in Latonia.

1855
01:37:41,956 --> 01:37:43,184
In a moment of carelessness.

1856
01:37:43,390 --> 01:37:45,290
He thought he had a sure thing
that time too,

1857
01:37:45,492 --> 01:37:47,187
but the horse forgot
what he came for.

1858
01:37:47,394 --> 01:37:50,921
Dan, on my bended knees,
win this race.

1859
01:37:51,131 --> 01:37:53,258
- All right, professor.
- So long, fella. Good luck.

1860
01:37:53,467 --> 01:37:54,934
But your horse just don't figure.

1861
01:37:55,135 --> 01:37:58,832
Any guy that puts his dough on him
just naturally believes in fairies.

1862
01:37:59,039 --> 01:38:00,529
Come on, Stupe.

1863
01:38:01,375 --> 01:38:03,172
Don't pay any attention to him, Dan.

1864
01:38:03,377 --> 01:38:05,777
- Good luck.
- Thanks, princess.

1865
01:38:07,047 --> 01:38:09,106
If Happy's right, I'm on my way
to Higginsville in the morning, huh?

1866
01:38:09,316 --> 01:38:11,307
Don't even think about it.
You'll win.

1867
01:38:11,518 --> 01:38:13,247
Thanks, princess.

1868
01:38:14,121 --> 01:38:15,418
Hey.

1869
01:38:15,823 --> 01:38:18,018
You're not supposed to cry
till after the race. Come on, here.

1870
01:38:18,225 --> 01:38:20,125
- What's the matter?
- Nothing.

1871
01:38:20,327 --> 01:38:21,885
Good luck.

1872
01:38:23,998 --> 01:38:26,592
Now, now, go watch the race. Go on.

1873
01:38:30,337 --> 01:38:32,305
I wish I knew how this thing
was going to end.

1874
01:38:37,544 --> 01:38:40,741
That Broadway Bill looks all right.
What's Doc Poole worried about?

1875
01:38:42,116 --> 01:38:44,141
- I don't think he was ever sick.
- He looks all right today.

1876
01:38:54,128 --> 01:38:55,356
Come right on in, miss.

1877
01:38:55,562 --> 01:38:57,086
Did you place a bet on number six,
Broadway Bill?

1878
01:38:57,298 --> 01:38:58,526
Sure crazy if you didn't.

1879
01:39:05,005 --> 01:39:06,233
Two dollars on Broadway Bill.

1880
01:39:06,440 --> 01:39:09,603
- Number six.
- Thanks.

1881
01:39:15,749 --> 01:39:17,512
Well, goodbye, sawbuck.

1882
01:39:17,718 --> 01:39:19,879
Might as well go crazy
with the rest of the world.

1883
01:39:20,087 --> 01:39:21,315
Oh, come on, come on.

1884
01:39:22,790 --> 01:39:26,521
Broadway Bill, number six,
on the schnozzola.

1885
01:39:30,998 --> 01:39:32,465
Who'd you bet on, Happy?

1886
01:39:32,666 --> 01:39:34,065
Gallant Lady, of course.

1887
01:39:34,268 --> 01:39:36,862
- Me too.
- Smart boy.

1888
01:39:38,272 --> 01:39:39,637
<i>Which horse is going to win?</i>

1889
01:39:39,840 --> 01:39:42,638
<i>Will it be Gallant Lady,</i>
<i>the temperamental favorite,</i>

1890
01:39:42,843 --> 01:39:44,708
<i>Sun Up, the great money horse,</i>

1891
01:39:44,912 --> 01:39:46,436
- <i>or will it be Broadway Bill?</i>
- Sit down.

1892
01:39:46,647 --> 01:39:49,582
<i>A colt that's never raced before</i>
<i>and who threw his jockey</i>

1893
01:39:49,783 --> 01:39:53,617
<i>the last time out and was</i>
<i>literally laughed off the track.</i>

1894
01:39:53,887 --> 01:39:56,014
<i>The wise ones say that his owner,</i>
<i>Dan Brooks,</i>

1895
01:39:56,223 --> 01:39:58,919
<i>has a screw loose somewhere</i>
<i>for entering him.</i>

1896
01:39:59,126 --> 01:40:02,061
<i>But we're going to keep our eyes</i>
<i>on Broadway Bill.</i>

1897
01:40:02,262 --> 01:40:04,389
- <i>For some mysterious reason,</i>
- Sit down.

1898
01:40:04,598 --> 01:40:06,862
<i>This unknown horse</i>
<i>has been receiving terrific support.</i>

1899
01:40:07,067 --> 01:40:10,525
<i>Almost overnight, the odds went down</i>
<i>from 100-to-1 to 6-to-1.</i>

1900
01:40:10,738 --> 01:40:12,706
- Yes, sir?
- Any whiskey in the house?

1901
01:40:12,906 --> 01:40:14,771
- No, sir.
- Get some.

1902
01:40:14,975 --> 01:40:16,636
Get some!

1903
01:40:22,683 --> 01:40:25,083
<i>The horses are at the gate now</i>
<i>and ready for the bell.</i>

1904
01:40:25,285 --> 01:40:26,513
<i>And what excitement.</i>

1905
01:40:26,720 --> 01:40:29,587
Sit still on Gallant Lady there.

1906
01:40:33,227 --> 01:40:34,455
Keep your eyes open, boys.

1907
01:40:34,661 --> 01:40:35,889
Anything's liable to happen
in this race.

1908
01:40:36,096 --> 01:40:38,326
Don't you forget to break fast, Bill.

1909
01:40:45,539 --> 01:40:47,530
<i>There they go.</i>

1910
01:40:52,780 --> 01:40:54,577
He's in the vanguard.

1911
01:40:55,215 --> 01:40:57,376
<i>Broadway Bill takes the lead</i>
<i>by two lengths...</i>

1912
01:41:00,287 --> 01:41:02,881
<i>... by a head, and Gotham Kid...</i>

1913
01:41:03,090 --> 01:41:05,991
<i>At the clubhouse turn,</i>
<i>Broadway Bill is in the lead</i>

1914
01:41:06,193 --> 01:41:09,685
<i>by four lengths.</i>
<i>Gallant Lady is second by one length.</i>

1915
01:41:09,897 --> 01:41:14,095
<i>Great Arab is third by two lengths,</i>
<i>and Sun Up...</i>

1916
01:41:14,301 --> 01:41:15,996
Quit pulling that horse.

1917
01:41:16,203 --> 01:41:17,431
Quit pulling him.

1918
01:41:17,638 --> 01:41:19,663
<i>... by one length,</i>
<i>and now dropping back,</i>

1919
01:41:19,873 --> 01:41:22,341
<i>as Gallant Lady takes the lead</i>
<i>by one length.</i>

1920
01:41:22,543 --> 01:41:23,976
<i>Gotham Kid is second...</i>

1921
01:41:24,178 --> 01:41:26,271
Give him his head, you little thief.
Let him go.

1922
01:41:35,789 --> 01:41:37,518
Bill.

1923
01:41:41,495 --> 01:41:43,486
Make way,
or I'll throw you over the fence.

1924
01:41:43,697 --> 01:41:44,925
Nuts to you.

1925
01:41:45,132 --> 01:41:47,100
We got a chance now.

1926
01:41:47,734 --> 01:41:50,134
Come on. What are you trying to do?
Let go of that bit.

1927
01:41:51,438 --> 01:41:53,531
Oh, he's got his tongue
over the bit now.

1928
01:41:53,740 --> 01:41:55,799
He can't stop you, Bill.
He can't stop you, Bill.

1929
01:41:58,946 --> 01:42:00,174
Let go of that bit.

1930
01:42:07,187 --> 01:42:08,677
Go, go, Bill. Go.

1931
01:42:09,356 --> 01:42:13,122
- <i>It's Gallant Lady and Sun Up...</i>
- Head for home, Bill. Go, boy.

1932
01:42:14,394 --> 01:42:17,295
<i>And here comes Broadway Bill,</i>
<i>moving between horses.</i>

1933
01:42:17,498 --> 01:42:18,931
<i>Look at this horse go.</i>

1934
01:42:20,100 --> 01:42:21,362
Come on, Broadway Bill.

1935
01:42:21,568 --> 01:42:23,126
Come on, Broadway Bill!

1936
01:42:27,307 --> 01:42:29,571
- Friend to the downtrodden!
- Come on, Broadway...

1937
01:42:29,776 --> 01:42:31,368
Come on!

1938
01:42:33,413 --> 01:42:36,314
Bill. Bill. Come on.

1939
01:42:39,653 --> 01:42:43,282
Come on, Broadway Bill.
Come on, Broadway Bill!

1940
01:42:43,490 --> 01:42:48,154
Yes, Broadway Bill! Come on.
Come on. Come on, Broadway Bill.

1941
01:42:54,601 --> 01:42:55,829
<i>They're coming into the stretch.</i>

1942
01:43:04,011 --> 01:43:07,708
<i>It's Gallant Lady, Sun Up</i>
<i>and Broadway Bill, head and head,</i>

1943
01:43:07,915 --> 01:43:11,009
- <i>all three together.</i>
- Come on, Bill. Come on! Come on.

1944
01:43:11,652 --> 01:43:13,176
Stay back there, will you!

1945
01:43:15,689 --> 01:43:16,986
Stay back, you rat.

1946
01:43:17,191 --> 01:43:18,658
He's got the bit.
I can't hold him, you nit.

1947
01:43:18,859 --> 01:43:21,054
Bill, Bill, Bill, Bill.

1948
01:43:30,404 --> 01:43:34,670
<i>It's Gallant Lady and Broadway Bill.</i>
<i>Sun Up is dropping back.</i>

1949
01:43:39,179 --> 01:43:41,613
Come on. Come on, Bill. Come on.

1950
01:43:41,815 --> 01:43:44,215
<i>It's Gallant Lady and Broadway Bill.</i>

1951
01:43:48,422 --> 01:43:50,788
<i>It's Broadway Bill and Gallant Lady.</i>

1952
01:43:53,393 --> 01:43:57,523
<i>They're coming down to the line</i>
<i>of finish, and Broadway Bill wins it!</i>

1953
01:44:00,567 --> 01:44:04,003
He did it. He did it.
Oh, he did it.

1954
01:44:04,204 --> 01:44:05,865
Oh, he did it. He did it.

1955
01:44:10,877 --> 01:44:12,504
Bill.

1956
01:44:12,713 --> 01:44:14,044
Bill.

1957
01:44:19,786 --> 01:44:22,254
<i>Back off that track, will you,</i>
<i>please. Now, don't get excited.</i>

1958
01:44:22,456 --> 01:44:23,718
<i>And keep back.</i>
<i>Everybody keep back.</i>

1959
01:44:23,924 --> 01:44:25,755
<i>Officers, see that everybody</i>
<i>keeps off that track.</i>

1960
01:44:25,959 --> 01:44:29,087
<i>You know how dangerous it is. Horses</i>
<i>will be getting back any minute.</i>

1961
01:44:29,296 --> 01:44:31,059
Fellows, can I get through?
Let me through, will you.

1962
01:44:31,265 --> 01:44:33,756
- Who are you?
- This is my horse, fellas.

1963
01:44:33,967 --> 01:44:37,596
<i>Officers, keep those people back.</i>
<i>Keep off the track, will you, please.</i>

1964
01:44:37,971 --> 01:44:39,871
Mr. Brooks.

1965
01:44:40,340 --> 01:44:42,535
Back it up, people. All right...

1966
01:44:42,743 --> 01:44:44,301
Let me through. Gangway.

1967
01:44:44,511 --> 01:44:46,172
- How's the boy?
- The boy's OK.

1968
01:44:46,380 --> 01:44:47,642
- Are you a doc?
- Yes, sir.

1969
01:44:47,848 --> 01:44:49,475
- Are you a veterinary?
- Yes, sir.

1970
01:44:49,683 --> 01:44:52,413
<i>The race was over.</i>
<i>He won and then he dropped.</i>

1971
01:45:00,794 --> 01:45:02,989
Too much for him.
Burst his heart.

1972
01:45:04,631 --> 01:45:07,464
He was dead, you might say,
when he hit the dirt.

1973
01:45:07,668 --> 01:45:09,363
Too bad.

1974
01:45:09,569 --> 01:45:11,264
A great horse.

1975
01:45:13,340 --> 01:45:14,864
Bill.

1976
01:45:17,477 --> 01:45:19,672
Will you hold it for a shot,
Mr. Brooks, please?

1977
01:45:19,880 --> 01:45:21,438
Officer, get those men out of there.

1978
01:45:21,648 --> 01:45:23,479
These old eyes have seen
some great horses, but...

1979
01:45:23,684 --> 01:45:24,912
Tough break, kid.

1980
01:45:25,152 --> 01:45:27,985
Come on, get back, will you, please.
Everybody, give us a little room here.

1981
01:45:28,188 --> 01:45:30,418
<i>Off the track, everybody.</i>

1982
01:46:21,074 --> 01:46:22,371
We're all grateful to Mr. Brooks

1983
01:46:22,576 --> 01:46:26,569
for permitting us to lay Broadway Bill
to rest here at the scene of his victory.

1984
01:46:27,414 --> 01:46:28,779
What he did yesterday afternoon

1985
01:46:28,982 --> 01:46:32,713
was to teach us all the true meaning
of courage and loyalty.

1986
01:46:32,986 --> 01:46:37,355
Broadway Bill only ran one race,
but he ran it well.

1987
01:46:37,557 --> 01:46:40,583
For he not only overcame the speed
of his brother horses,

1988
01:46:40,794 --> 01:46:43,194
but he had to overcome the greed
in us human beings.

1989
01:46:43,997 --> 01:46:47,558
We should all feel humble
and a little ashamed that a horse

1990
01:46:47,768 --> 01:46:50,293
should teach us such a lesson
in honesty.

1991
01:46:50,804 --> 01:46:53,329
If we profit by such an example,

1992
01:46:53,540 --> 01:46:55,701
then racing will be something
more than a sport,

1993
01:46:56,543 --> 01:46:59,569
and Broadway Bill
will never be forgotten.

1994
01:47:00,046 --> 01:47:01,946
Mr. Brooks.

1995
01:48:05,278 --> 01:48:09,214
Well, I guess I'll be
saying goodbye, Dan.

1996
01:48:10,016 --> 01:48:12,450
You'll be going back home
to Higginsville, huh?

1997
01:48:14,054 --> 01:48:16,147
But not you. You won't.

1998
01:48:16,356 --> 01:48:17,983
No.

1999
01:48:19,626 --> 01:48:21,992
I'll be on my way, I guess.

2000
01:48:23,697 --> 01:48:25,494
Good luck.

2001
01:48:26,466 --> 01:48:28,263
Princess, you've been swell.

2002
01:48:28,468 --> 01:48:30,732
- You've helped me over a...
- Thanks, Dan.

2003
01:48:32,172 --> 01:48:34,197
Oh, there's Dad.

2004
01:48:37,611 --> 01:48:39,044
Dan.

2005
01:48:40,213 --> 01:48:41,771
J.L.

2006
01:48:42,182 --> 01:48:44,343
Margaret come with you?

2007
01:48:44,918 --> 01:48:46,613
No, she didn't.

2008
01:48:46,820 --> 01:48:50,051
You see, Margaret sort of counted
on your coming back to Higginsville,

2009
01:48:50,257 --> 01:48:52,725
- now that Broadway Bill...
- Yeah.

2010
01:48:52,926 --> 01:48:55,724
I guess she figured
this would be the break.

2011
01:48:56,062 --> 01:48:58,053
I'm not going back
to Higginsville, J.L.

2012
01:48:59,432 --> 01:49:01,900
I... I don't know.

2013
01:49:02,369 --> 01:49:04,633
Nothing matters much anymore.

2014
01:49:04,838 --> 01:49:07,068
Just take care of the princess, huh?

2015
01:49:18,318 --> 01:49:20,980
That's my decision, and it's final.

2016
01:49:21,187 --> 01:49:22,745
But, Father, what's come over you?

2017
01:49:22,956 --> 01:49:24,583
You can't sell the paper-box factory.

2018
01:49:24,791 --> 01:49:26,986
We've only been married for
two months. It isn't fair to Bertie.

2019
01:49:27,193 --> 01:49:29,718
- Yeah.
- Bertie.

2020
01:49:30,564 --> 01:49:32,691
And I'm selling the ironworks,

2021
01:49:32,899 --> 01:49:36,198
the lampshade plant
and next and last, the bank.

2022
01:49:36,403 --> 01:49:37,961
- No, no, not the bank.
- No, not the bank.

2023
01:49:38,171 --> 01:49:40,571
- The bank?
- Well, what will become of us?

2024
01:49:40,807 --> 01:49:42,035
You?

2025
01:49:42,776 --> 01:49:45,006
You'll have to go to work.

2026
01:50:00,360 --> 01:50:02,692
- It's Dan.
- Princess.

2027
01:50:02,896 --> 01:50:05,364
Hey, it's Mr. Brooks, sir.

2028
01:50:05,565 --> 01:50:09,126
"Release the princess
from the dark tower", he says.

2029
01:50:18,478 --> 01:50:21,709
Well, go on. Go on.
Don't be an idiot like your sister.

2030
01:50:21,915 --> 01:50:23,610
Princess!

2031
01:50:29,522 --> 01:50:31,490
Looking for someone?

2032
01:50:32,459 --> 01:50:33,790
Not anymore, I'm not.

2033
01:50:33,994 --> 01:50:37,452
Look, Broadway Bill II
and the Princess.

2034
01:50:37,697 --> 01:50:40,291
- Oh, Dan.
- Come on, we're off to Santa Anita.

2035
01:50:40,934 --> 01:50:43,232
Get aboard, here we go.
Remember Whitey?

2036
01:50:43,436 --> 01:50:45,529
- Hi, Whitey. Hi, Skeeter.
- Hi there.

2037
01:50:47,641 --> 01:50:50,007
Goodbye, Dad.
Goodbye, Johnson.

2038
01:50:52,145 --> 01:50:54,875
Oh, I'm so glad you came back.

2039
01:51:00,754 --> 01:51:03,348
Hey! Wait for me!

